# Prime Number Checker in Rust

## Implementation

```rust
fn is_prime(n: u64) -> bool {
    if n < 2 {
        return false;
    }
    if n == 2 {
        return true;
    }
    if n % 2 == 0 {
        return false;
    }
    if n == 3 {
        return true;
    }
    if n % 3 == 0 {
        return false;
    }

    // Check divisors of the form 6k ± 1 up to √n
    let mut i = 5u64;
    while i * i <= n {
        if n % i == 0 || n % (i + 2) == 0 {
            return false;
        }
        i += 6;
    }

    true
}

fn main() {
    let test_cases = [
        0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 10, 13, 17, 20, 97, 100, 7919, 7920,
    ];

    println!("{:<10} {}", "Number", "Prime?");
    println!("{}", "-".repeat(20));

    for &n in &test_cases {
        println!("{:<10} {}", n, is_prime(n));
    }
}
```

## How It Works

The algorithm uses several optimizations:

| Step | Optimization | Reason |
|------|-------------|--------|
| `n < 2` | Return false | By definition |
| `n == 2` | Return true | Only even prime |
| `n % 2 == 0` | Return false | Eliminates all even numbers |
| `n % 3 == 0` | Return false | Eliminates multiples of 3 |
| `6k ± 1` loop | Check up to √n | All primes > 3 have this form |

### The 6k ± 1 Pattern

All primes greater than 3 can be expressed as `6k - 1` or `6k + 1` (i.e., `5, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, ...`). This lets us skip **2/3 of all candidates**, only checking numbers of the form `6k ± 1`.

## Expected Output

```
Number     Prime?
--------------------
0          false
1          false
2          true
3          true
4          false
5          true
10         false
13         true
17         true
20         false
97         true
100        false
7919       true
7920       false
```

