## Key Design Decisions

| Decision | Rationale |
|---|---|
| `Vec<T>` as backing store | O(1) amortized push/pop, contiguous memory |
| `Result<T, StackError>` returns | Explicit error handling instead of panics |
| `Option<usize>` capacity | Supports both bounded and unbounded stacks |
| Generic `<T>` | Works with any type, no trait bounds on core ops |
| Custom `StackError` enum | Distinguishes overflow, underflow, and empty |

## Complexity

| Operation | Time | Space |
|---|---|---|
| `push` | O(1) amortized | O(1) |
| `pop` | O(1) | O(1) |
| `peek` | O(1) | O(1) |
| `contains` | O(n) | O(1) |
| `iter` | O(n) | O(1) |

# Palindrome Checker in Rust

## Implementation

```rust
fn is_palindrome(s: &str) -> bool {
    let chars: Vec<char> = s.chars().collect();
    let len = chars.len();

    for i in 0..len / 2 {
        if chars[i] != chars[len - 1 - i] {
            return false;
        }
    }

    true
}

/// Case-insensitive palindrome check, ignoring non-alphanumeric characters.
fn is_palindrome_strict(s: &str) -> bool {
    let filtered: Vec<char> = s
        .chars()
        .filter(|c| c.is_alphanumeric())
        .map(|c| c.to_lowercase().next().unwrap())
        .collect();

    let len = filtered.len();

    for i in 0..len / 2 {
        if filtered[i] != filtered[len - 1 - i] {
            return false;
        }
    }

    true
}

fn main() {
    let test_cases = vec![
        ("racecar", true),
        ("hello", false),
        ("level", true),
        ("", true),
        ("a", true),
        ("ab", false),
        ("A man a plan a canal Panama", true),
        ("Was it a car or a cat I saw", true),
        ("Not a palindrome", false),
        ("Madam", true),
    ];

    println!("{:<35} {:<10} {:<10}", "Input", "Basic", "Strict");
    println!("{}", "-".repeat(55));

    for (input, expected_strict) in &test_cases {
        let basic = is_palindrome(input);
        let strict = is_palindrome_strict(input);

        let strict_mark = if strict == *expected_strict { "✓" } else { "✗" };

        println!(
            "{:<35} {:<10} {:<10}",
            format!("\"{}\"", input),
            basic,
            format!("{} {}", strict, strict_mark)
        );
    }
}
