## Key Design Decisions

| Decision | Reason |
|---|---|
| `mid = low + (high - low) / 2` | Prevents integer overflow vs `(low + high) / 2` |
| `high = arr.len()` (exclusive) | Half-open ranges `[low, high)` eliminate off-by-one errors |
| Generic over `T: Ord` | Works with any totally-ordered type (integers, strings, etc.) |
| `Option<usize>` return type | Idiomatic Rust — no sentinel values like `-1` |
| `match` on `Ordering` | Exhaustive and readable; compiler ensures all cases handled |

# Flatten a Nested List in Rust

## Implementation

Here's a complete implementation that handles arbitrarily deeply nested lists using a recursive enum type:

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
enum NestedList<T> {
    Value(T),
    List(Vec<NestedList<T>>),
}

impl<T: Clone> NestedList<T> {
    /// Flatten a nested list into a single Vec<T>
    fn flatten(&self) -> Vec<T> {
        let mut result = Vec::new();
        self.flatten_into(&mut result);
        result
    }

    fn flatten_into(&self, result: &mut Vec<T>) {
        match self {
            NestedList::Value(v) => result.push(v.clone()),
            NestedList::List(items) => {
                for item in items {
                    item.flatten_into(result);
                }
            }
        }
    }
}

/// Flatten a Vec of NestedList items into a single Vec<T>
fn flatten_nested<T: Clone>(nested: &[NestedList<T>]) -> Vec<T> {
    let mut result = Vec::new();
    for item in nested {
        item.flatten_into(&mut result);
    }
    result
}

fn main() {
    // Example 1: Simple nested list
    // Represents: [1, [2, 3], [4, [5, 6]]]
    let nested = NestedList::List(vec![
        NestedList::Value(1),
        NestedList::List(vec![
            NestedList::Value(2),
            NestedList::Value(3),
        ]),
        NestedList::List(vec![
            NestedList::Value(4),
            NestedList::List(vec![
                NestedList::Value(5),
                NestedList::Value(6),
            ]),
        ]),
    ]);

    let flat = nested.flatten();
    println!("Example 1: {:?}", flat);
    // Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]

    // Example 2: Deeply nested
    // Represents: [[[[1], 2], 3], 4]
    let deep = NestedList::List(vec![
        NestedList::List(vec![
            NestedList::List(vec![
                NestedList::List(vec![
                    NestedList::Value(1),
                ]),
                NestedList::Value(2),
            ]),
            NestedList::Value(3),
        ]),
        NestedList::Value(4),
    ]);

    let flat_deep = deep.flatten();
    println!("Example 2: {:?}", flat_deep);
    // Output: [1, 2, 3, 4]

    // Example 3: Using flatten_nested on a slice
    let items = vec![
        NestedList::Value(10),
        NestedList::List(vec![
            NestedList::Value(20),
            NestedList::Value(30),
        ]),
        NestedList::Value(40),
    ];

    let flat_slice = flatten_nested(&items);
    println!("Example 3: {:?}", flat_slice);
    // Output: [10, 20, 30, 40]

    // Example 4: With strings
    let strings = NestedList::List(vec![
        NestedList::Value("hello"),
        NestedList::List(vec![
            NestedList::Value("world"),
            NestedList::Value("foo"),
        ]),
        NestedList::Value("bar"),
    ]);

    let flat_strings = strings.flatten();
    println!("Example 4: {:?}", flat_strings);
    // Output: ["hello", "world", "foo", "bar"]
}

