## How It Works

### Token Bucket Algorithm

```
┌─────────────────────────────────┐
│         Token Bucket            │
│                                 │
│  refill_rate ──▶ [●●●●●○○○○○]  │
│  (tokens/sec)    └─── tokens ──┘│
│                       │         │
│                   acquire(n)    │
│                       │         │
│               ✅ ok / ❌ limited│
└─────────────────────────────────┘
```

| Concept | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| **Capacity** | Maximum tokens (burst size) |
| **Refill rate** | Tokens added per second |
| **`try_acquire`** | Non-blocking; returns error with wait time |
| **`acquire`** | Blocking; sleeps until tokens available |

### Key Design Decisions

| Decision | Rationale |
|----------|-----------|
| `f64` for tokens | Smooth fractional refills between calls |
| `Arc<Mutex<>>` | Safe sharing across threads |
| `Instant`-based refill | No background thread needed (lazy evaluation) |
| Builder pattern | Ergonomic construction with named parameters |
| `Clone` on `TokenBucket` | Clones share the same underlying state |

# Bounded Blocking Queue in Rust

A thread-safe bounded blocking queue where:
- **Producers block** when the queue is full
- **Consumers block** when the queue is empty

## Implementation

```rust
use std::collections::VecDeque;
use std::sync::{Arc, Condvar, Mutex};
use std::time::Duration;

/// A thread-safe bounded blocking queue.
pub struct BoundedBlockingQueue<T> {
    inner: Arc<QueueInner<T>>,
}

struct QueueInner<T> {
    data: Mutex<QueueData<T>>,
    not_full: Condvar,
    not_empty: Condvar,
}

struct QueueData<T> {
    buffer: VecDeque<T>,
    capacity: usize,
    closed: bool,
}

/// Error types for queue operations.
#[derive(Debug, PartialEq)]
pub enum QueueError {
    /// The queue has been closed.
    Closed,
    /// A timed operation timed out.
    Timeout,
    /// The queue is full (non-blocking push).
    Full,
    /// The queue is empty (non-blocking pop).
    Empty,
}

impl std::fmt::Display for QueueError {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut std::fmt::Formatter<'_>) -> std::fmt::Result {
        match self {
            QueueError::Closed => write!(f, "queue is closed"),
            QueueError::Timeout => write!(f, "operation timed out"),
            QueueError::Full => write!(f, "queue is full"),
            QueueError::Empty => write!(f, "queue is empty"),
        }
    }
}

impl std::error::Error for QueueError {}

impl<T> BoundedBlockingQueue<T> {
    /// Creates a new bounded blocking queue with the given capacity.
    ///
    /// # Panics
    /// Panics if `capacity` is 0.
    pub fn new(capacity: usize) -> Self {
        assert!(capacity > 0, "capacity must be greater than 0");
        BoundedBlockingQueue {
            inner: Arc::new(QueueInner {
                data: Mutex::new(QueueData {
                    buffer: VecDeque::with_capacity(capacity),
                    capacity,
                    closed: false,
                }),
                not_full: Condvar::new(),
                not_empty: Condvar::new(),
            }),
        }
    }

    /// Pushes an item onto the queue, blocking until space is available.
    ///
    /// Returns `Err(QueueError::Closed)` if the queue has been closed.
    pub fn push(&self, item: T) -> Result<(), QueueError> {
        let mut data = self.inner.data.lock().unwrap();

        // Wait until there is space or the queue is closed.
        loop {
            if data.closed {
                return Err(QueueError::Closed);
            }
            if data.buffer.len() < data.capacity {
                break;
            }
            data = self.inner.not_full.wait(data).unwrap();
        }

        data.buffer.push_back(item);
        // Wake one waiting consumer.
        self.inner.not_empty.notify_one();
        Ok(())
    }

    /// Tries to push an item without blocking.
    ///
    /// Returns `Err(QueueError::Full)` if the queue is full.
    pub fn try_push(&self, item: T) -> Result<(), QueueError> {
        let mut data = self.inner.data.lock().unwrap();

        if data.closed {
            return Err(QueueError::Closed);
        }
        if data.buffer.len() >= data.capacity {
            return Err(QueueError::Full);
        }

        data.buffer.push_back(item);
        self.inner.not_empty.notify_one();
        Ok(())
    }

    /// Pushes an item, blocking for at most `timeout`.
    ///
    /// Returns `Err(QueueError::Timeout)` if the timeout expires.
    pub fn push_timeout(&self, item: T, timeout: Duration) -> Result<(), QueueError> {
        let mut data = self.inner.data.lock().unwrap();
        let mut remaining = timeout;
        let start = std::time::Instant::now();

        loop {
            if data.closed {
                return Err(QueueError::Closed);
            }
            if data.buffer.len() < data.capacity {
                break;
            }

            let (new_data, wait_result) =
                self.inner.not_full.wait_timeout(data, remaining).unwrap();
            data = new_data;

            if wait_result.timed_out() {
                return Err(QueueError::Timeout);
            }

            // Recalculate remaining time to guard against spurious wakeups.
            let elapsed = start.elapsed();
            if elapsed >= timeout {
                return Err(QueueError::Timeout);
            }
            remaining = timeout - elapsed;
        }

        data.buffer.push_back(item);
        self.inner.not_empty.notify_one();
        Ok(())
    }

    /// Pops an item from the queue, blocking until one is available.
    ///
    /// Returns `Err(QueueError::Closed)` if the queue is closed and empty.
    pub fn pop(&self) -> Result<T, QueueError> {
        let mut data = self.inner.data.lock().unwrap();

        loop {
            if let Some(item) = data.buffer.pop_front() {
                // Wake one waiting producer.
                self.inner.not_full.notify_one();
                return Ok(item);
            }
            if data.closed {
                return Err(QueueError::Closed);
            }
            data = self.inner.not_empty.wait(data).unwrap();
        }
    }

    /// Tries to pop an item without blocking.
    ///
    /// Returns `Err(QueueError::Empty)` if the queue is empty.
    pub fn try_pop(&self) -> Result<T, QueueError> {
        let mut data = self.inner.data.lock().unwrap();

        if let Some(item) = data.buffer.pop_front() {
            self.inner.not_full.notify_one();
            return Ok(item);
        }
        if data.closed {
            return Err(QueueError::Closed);
        }
        Err(QueueError::Empty)
    }

    /// Pops an item, blocking for at most `timeout`.
    ///
    /// Returns `Err(QueueError::Timeout)` if the timeout expires.
    pub fn pop_timeout(&self, timeout: Duration) -> Result<T, QueueError> {
        let mut data = self.inner.data.lock().unwrap();
        let mut remaining = timeout;
        let start = std::time::Instant::now();

        loop {
            if let Some(item) = data.buffer.pop_front() {
                self.inner.not_full.notify_one();
                return Ok(item);
            }
            if data.closed {
                return Err(QueueError::Closed);
            }

            let (new_data, wait_result) = self
                .inner
                .not_empty
                .wait_timeout(data, remaining)
                .unwrap();
            data = new_data;

            if wait_result.timed_out() {
                return Err(QueueError::Timeout);
            }

            let elapsed = start.elapsed();
            if elapsed >= timeout {
                return Err(QueueError::Timeout);
            }
            remaining = timeout - elapsed;
        }
    }

    /// Closes the queue. All blocked and future operations will return errors.
    /// Items already in the queue can still be drained via `pop`.
    pub fn close(&self) {
        let mut data = self.inner.data.lock().unwrap();
        data.closed = true;
        // Wake all waiting threads so they can observe the closed state.
        self.inner.not_empty.notify_all();
        self.inner.not_full.notify_all();
    }

    /// Returns the number of items currently in the queue.
    pub fn len(&self) -> usize {
        self.inner.data.lock().unwrap().buffer.len()
    }

    /// Returns `true` if the queue is empty.
    pub fn is_empty(&self) -> bool {
        self.len() == 0
    }

    /// Returns the maximum capacity of the queue.
    pub fn capacity(&self) -> usize {
        self.inner.data.lock().unwrap().capacity
    }

    /// Returns `true` if the queue is closed.
    pub fn is_closed(&self) -> bool {
        self.inner.data.lock().unwrap().closed
    }
}

/// Allows the queue to be cheaply cloned and shared across threads.
impl<T> Clone for BoundedBlockingQueue<T> {
    fn clone(&self) -> Self {
        BoundedBlockingQueue {
            inner: Arc::clone(&self.inner),
        }
    }
}

// SAFETY: The queue is safe to send across threads because we protect all
// access with a Mutex.
unsafe impl<T: Send> Send for BoundedBlockingQueue<T> {}
unsafe impl<T: Send> Sync for BoundedBlockingQueue<T> {}

