## How It Works

### Data Layout

```
BoundedBlockingQueue<T>
  └── Arc<QueueInner<T>>
        ├── Mutex<QueueData<T>>   ← single lock guards all state
        │     ├── VecDeque<T>     ← the ring buffer
        │     ├── capacity: usize
        │     └── closed: bool
        ├── Condvar not_full      ← signalled when an item is removed
        └── Condvar not_empty     ← signalled when an item is added
```

### Key Design Decisions

| Decision | Rationale |
|---|---|
| Single `Mutex` + two `Condvar`s | Classic two-condition monitor pattern — minimal complexity, correct |
| `VecDeque` as ring buffer | O(1) push/pop from both ends, avoids shifting |
| `closed` flag inside the lock | Prevents TOCTOU races between close and wait |
| `Arc` for shared ownership | Enables cheap `Clone` to share across threads |
| Spurious-wakeup guard in timeout paths | Recalculates remaining time after each wakeup |
| Drain-on-close semantics | Consumers can flush the queue before seeing `Closed` |

### Operation Summary

- **`push`** — blocks if full, errors if closed
- **`pop`** — blocks if empty, errors only when *both* closed *and* empty (allows drain)
- **`try_push`/`try_pop`** — non-blocking variants
- **`push_timeout`/`pop_timeout`** — deadline-bounded variants
- **`close`** — signals all waiters; existing items remain drainable

# Arithmetic Expression Evaluator in Rust

This implementation supports:
- Basic operations: `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, `%`
- Exponentiation: `^`
- Unary minus: `-3`
- Parentheses for grouping
- Floating-point numbers
- Proper operator precedence

## Implementation

```rust
use std::fmt;
use std::io::{self, BufRead, Write};
use std::iter::Peekable;
use std::str::Chars;

// ─── Error Type ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq)]
pub enum EvalError {
    UnexpectedChar(char),
    UnexpectedEnd,
    UnexpectedToken(Token),
    DivisionByZero,
    MismatchedParentheses,
}

impl fmt::Display for EvalError {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter<'_>) -> fmt::Result {
        match self {
            EvalError::UnexpectedChar(c) => write!(f, "Unexpected character: '{}'", c),
            EvalError::UnexpectedEnd => write!(f, "Unexpected end of expression"),
            EvalError::UnexpectedToken(t) => write!(f, "Unexpected token: {:?}", t),
            EvalError::DivisionByZero => write!(f, "Division by zero"),
            EvalError::MismatchedParentheses => write!(f, "Mismatched parentheses"),
        }
    }
}

// ─── Tokens ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq)]
pub enum Token {
    Number(f64),
    Plus,
    Minus,
    Star,
    Slash,
    Percent,
    Caret,
    LParen,
    RParen,
}

// ─── Lexer ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

pub struct Lexer<'a> {
    chars: Peekable<Chars<'a>>,
}

impl<'a> Lexer<'a> {
    pub fn new(input: &'a str) -> Self {
        Lexer {
            chars: input.chars().peekable(),
        }
    }

    fn skip_whitespace(&mut self) {
        while self.chars.peek().map_or(false, |c| c.is_whitespace()) {
            self.chars.next();
        }
    }

    fn read_number(&mut self, first: char) -> Result<Token, EvalError> {
        let mut s = String::from(first);

        while let Some(&c) = self.chars.peek() {
            if c.is_ascii_digit() || c == '.' {
                s.push(c);
                self.chars.next();
            } else {
                break;
            }
        }

        // Support scientific notation: e.g. 1.5e10, 2e-3
        if let Some(&c) = self.chars.peek() {
            if c == 'e' || c == 'E' {
                s.push(c);
                self.chars.next();
                if let Some(&sign) = self.chars.peek() {
                    if sign == '+' || sign == '-' {
                        s.push(sign);
                        self.chars.next();
                    }
                }
                while let Some(&c) = self.chars.peek() {
                    if c.is_ascii_digit() {
                        s.push(c);
                        self.chars.next();
                    } else {
                        break;
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        s.parse::<f64>()
            .map(Token::Number)
            .map_err(|_| EvalError::UnexpectedChar(s.chars().next().unwrap()))
    }

    pub fn tokenize(&mut self) -> Result<Vec<Token>, EvalError> {
        let mut tokens = Vec::new();

        loop {
            self.skip_whitespace();
            match self.chars.peek().copied() {
                None => break,
                Some(c) => {
                    self.chars.next();
                    let tok = match c {
                        '0'..='9' | '.' => self.read_number(c)?,
                        '+' => Token::Plus,
                        '-' => Token::Minus,
                        '*' => Token::Star,
                        '/' => Token::Slash,
                        '%' => Token::Percent,
                        '^' => Token::Caret,
                        '(' => Token::LParen,
                        ')' => Token::RParen,
                        other => return Err(EvalError::UnexpectedChar(other)),
                    };
                    tokens.push(tok);
                }
            }
        }

        Ok(tokens)
    }
}

// ─── Parser / Evaluator ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Grammar (operator precedence, low → high):
//   expr    = term   { ('+' | '-') term   }
//   term    = factor { ('*' | '/' | '%') factor }
//   factor  = base   { '^' factor }          ← right-associative
//   base    = '-' base | '(' expr ')' | NUMBER

pub struct Parser {
    tokens: Vec<Token>,
    pos: usize,
}

impl Parser {
    pub fn new(tokens: Vec<Token>) -> Self {
        Parser { tokens, pos: 0 }
    }

    // ── helpers ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

    fn peek(&self) -> Option<&Token> {
        self.tokens.get(self.pos)
    }

    fn advance(&mut self) -> Option<&Token> {
        let tok = self.tokens.get(self.pos);
        self.pos += 1;
        tok
    }

    fn expect_rparen(&mut self) -> Result<(), EvalError> {
        match self.advance() {
            Some(Token::RParen) => Ok(()),
            Some(t) => Err(EvalError::UnexpectedToken(t.clone())),
            None => Err(EvalError::MismatchedParentheses),
        }
    }

    // ── grammar rules ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

    /// expr = term { ('+' | '-') term }
    fn parse_expr(&mut self) -> Result<f64, EvalError> {
        let mut left = self.parse_term()?;

        loop {
            match self.peek() {
                Some(Token::Plus) => {
                    self.advance();
                    left += self.parse_term()?;
                }
                Some(Token::Minus) => {
                    self.advance();
                    left -= self.parse_term()?;
                }
                _ => break,
            }
        }

        Ok(left)
    }

    /// term = factor { ('*' | '/' | '%') factor }
    fn parse_term(&mut self) -> Result<f64, EvalError> {
        let mut left = self.parse_factor()?;

        loop {
            match self.peek() {
                Some(Token::Star) => {
                    self.advance();
                    left *= self.parse_factor()?;
                }
                Some(Token::Slash) => {
                    self.advance();
                    let right = self.parse_factor()?;
                    if right == 0.0 {
                        return Err(EvalError::DivisionByZero);
                    }
                    left /= right;
                }
                Some(Token::Percent) => {
                    self.advance();
                    let right = self.parse_factor()?;
                    if right == 0.0 {
                        return Err(EvalError::DivisionByZero);
                    }
                    left %= right;
                }
                _ => break,
            }
        }

        Ok(left)
    }

    /// factor = base { '^' factor }   (right-associative)
    fn parse_factor(&mut self) -> Result<f64, EvalError> {
        let base = self.parse_base()?;

        if let Some(Token::Caret) = self.peek() {
            self.advance();
            let exp = self.parse_factor()?; // right-recursive → right-associative
            Ok(base.powf(exp))
        } else {
            Ok(base)
        }
    }

    /// base = '-' base | '(' expr ')' | NUMBER
    fn parse_base(&mut self) -> Result<f64, EvalError> {
        match self.peek().cloned() {
            Some(Token::Minus) => {
                self.advance();
                let val = self.parse_base()?;
                Ok(-val)
            }
            Some(Token::Plus) => {
                self.advance();
                self.parse_base()
            }
            Some(Token::LParen) => {
                self.advance();
                let val = self.parse_expr()?;
                self.expect_rparen()?;
                Ok(val)
            }
            Some(Token::Number(n)) => {
                self.advance();
                Ok(n)
            }
            Some(tok) => Err(EvalError::UnexpectedToken(tok)),
            None => Err(EvalError::UnexpectedEnd),
        }
    }

    // ── public entry point ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

    pub fn evaluate(&mut self) -> Result<f64, EvalError> {
        if self.tokens.is_empty() {
            return Err(EvalError::UnexpectedEnd);
        }

        let result = self.parse_expr()?;

        // Make sure all tokens were consumed
        if let Some(tok) = self.peek() {
            return Err(EvalError::UnexpectedToken(tok.clone()));
        }

        Ok(result)
    }
}

// ─── Public API ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

pub fn evaluate(input: &str) -> Result<f64, EvalError> {
    let tokens = Lexer::new(input).tokenize()?;
    Parser::new(tokens).evaluate()
}

// ─── REPL ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

fn main() {
    let stdin = io::stdin();
    print!("Arithmetic Evaluator  (type 'quit' to exit)\n\n");

    loop {
        print!("> ");
        io::stdout().flush().unwrap();

        let mut line = String::new();
        match stdin.lock().read_line(&mut line) {
            Ok(0) | Err(_) => break, // EOF
            Ok(_) => {}
        }

        let input = line.trim();
        if input.eq_ignore_ascii_case("quit") || input.eq_ignore_ascii_case("exit") {
            break;
        }
        if input.is_empty() {
            continue;
        }

        match evaluate(input) {
            Ok(result) => {
                // Print as integer when the value is whole
                if result.fract() == 0.0 && result.abs() < 1e15 {
                    println!("= {}", result as i64);
                } else {
                    println!("= {}", result);
                }
            }
            Err(e) => eprintln!("Error: {}", e),
        }
    }
}

