## Key Design Decisions

| Decision | Rationale |
|----------|-----------|
| `tokio::mpsc` channels | Simulate network RPCs in-process without actual networking |
| Randomized election timeouts (150–300ms) | Reduces split-vote probability per Raft paper |
| Heartbeat every 50ms | Well below minimum election timeout to prevent spurious elections |
| `saturating_duration_since` | Avoids panics from `Instant` arithmetic when deadline already passed |
| Separate `PersistentState` struct | Makes it clear which state must survive crashes in a real system |

# Batcher's Odd-Even Mergesort in Rust

## Overview

Batcher's odd-even mergesort is a parallel sorting network algorithm that sorts by repeatedly merging odd and even indexed subsequences. It has O(log²n) depth and O(n log²n) total comparisons.

## Implementation

```rust
/// Batcher's Odd-Even Mergesort implementation
/// Works as a sorting network - the compare-and-swap operations can be
/// executed in parallel within each "round"

/// Compare and swap two elements if they're out of order
fn compare_and_swap<T: Ord>(arr: &mut [T], i: usize, j: usize) {
    if arr[i] > arr[j] {
        arr.swap(i, j);
    }
}

/// Odd-even merge two sorted halves:
/// - lo: starting index
/// - hi: ending index (exclusive)
/// - step: stride between elements being compared
fn odd_even_merge<T: Ord>(arr: &mut [T], lo: usize, hi: usize, step: usize) {
    let len = hi - lo;
    if step >= len {
        return;
    }

    let double_step = step * 2;

    if double_step >= len {
        // Base case: only one comparison needed
        compare_and_swap(arr, lo, lo + step);
    } else {
        // Recursively merge odd and even indexed subsequences
        odd_even_merge(arr, lo, hi, double_step);
        odd_even_merge(arr, lo + step, hi, double_step);

        // Compare and swap adjacent pairs in the interleaved result
        let mut i = lo + step;
        while i + step < hi {
            compare_and_swap(arr, i, i + step);
            i += double_step;
        }
    }
}

/// Recursive odd-even mergesort
/// - lo: starting index
/// - hi: ending index (exclusive)
fn odd_even_mergesort_recursive<T: Ord>(arr: &mut [T], lo: usize, hi: usize) {
    if hi - lo < 2 {
        return; // Base case: 0 or 1 elements
    }

    let mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2;

    // Sort the two halves
    odd_even_mergesort_recursive(arr, lo, mid);
    odd_even_mergesort_recursive(arr, mid, hi);

    // Merge the sorted halves
    odd_even_merge(arr, lo, hi, 1);
}

/// Public API: sort a mutable slice using Batcher's odd-even mergesort
pub fn odd_even_mergesort<T: Ord>(arr: &mut [T]) {
    let len = arr.len();
    if len < 2 {
        return;
    }
    odd_even_mergesort_recursive(arr, 0, len);
}

// ─── Iterative / sorting-network version ─────────────────────────────────────

/// Build the sequence of (i, j) comparator pairs for a slice of length n.
/// All pairs within the same "round" can be executed in parallel.
/// Returns pairs grouped by round for illustration; here we flatten them.
pub fn build_comparator_network(n: usize) -> Vec<(usize, usize)> {
    let mut pairs = Vec::new();
    build_merge_pairs(0, n, 1, &mut pairs);
    pairs
}

fn build_merge_pairs(lo: usize, hi: usize, step: usize, pairs: &mut Vec<(usize, usize)>) {
    let len = hi - lo;
    if step >= len {
        return;
    }
    let double_step = step * 2;
    if double_step >= len {
        pairs.push((lo, lo + step));
    } else {
        build_merge_pairs(lo, hi, double_step, pairs);
        build_merge_pairs(lo + step, hi, double_step, pairs);
        let mut i = lo + step;
        while i + step < hi {
            pairs.push((i, i + step));
            i += double_step;
        }
    }
}

/// Sort using a pre-built comparator network (useful for fixed-size inputs)
pub fn sort_with_network<T: Ord>(arr: &mut [T], network: &[(usize, usize)]) {
    for &(i, j) in network {
        compare_and_swap(arr, i, j);
    }
}

