## Key Design Decisions

| Aspect | Choice |
|--------|--------|
| **Lexing** | Hand-written single-pass lexer |
| **Parsing** | Recursive descent + Pratt precedence climbing for expressions |
| **Error handling** | `Result<_, String>` throughout |
| **AST** | Typed enums for all node kinds |
| **Operator precedence** | `OR(1) < AND(2) < comparison(3-4)` |

## Running

```bash
# Run with output
cargo run

# Run all 21 tests
cargo test
```

The parser correctly handles operator precedence (e.g. `AND` binds tighter than `OR`), parenthesised sub-expressions, postfix operators (`IS NULL`, `BETWEEN`, `IN`, `LIKE`), and multi-token keywords (`LEFT OUTER JOIN`, `GROUP BY`, `ORDER BY`).

# Lamport Timestamps for Distributed Ordering in Rust

## Overview

Lamport timestamps provide a logical clock mechanism for ordering events in distributed systems, establishing a "happens-before" relationship between events across multiple processes.

## Implementation

```rust
use std::collections::{BinaryHeap, HashMap};
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};
use std::cmp::Ordering;
use std::fmt;

// ============================================================
// Core Lamport Clock
// ============================================================

/// A thread-safe Lamport logical clock.
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct LamportClock {
    time: Arc<Mutex<u64>>,
    process_id: u32,
}

impl LamportClock {
    pub fn new(process_id: u32) -> Self {
        Self {
            time: Arc::new(Mutex::new(0)),
            process_id,
        }
    }

    /// Increment clock on a local event. Returns the new timestamp.
    pub fn tick(&self) -> u64 {
        let mut t = self.time.lock().unwrap();
        *t += 1;
        *t
    }

    /// Update clock on message send. Returns the timestamp to attach to the message.
    pub fn send(&self) -> u64 {
        self.tick()
    }

    /// Update clock on message receive. Returns the updated local timestamp.
    /// Rule: time = max(local, received) + 1
    pub fn receive(&self, received_timestamp: u64) -> u64 {
        let mut t = self.time.lock().unwrap();
        *t = (*t).max(received_timestamp) + 1;
        *t
    }

    /// Read the current time without advancing it.
    pub fn current_time(&self) -> u64 {
        *self.time.lock().unwrap()
    }

    pub fn process_id(&self) -> u32 {
        self.process_id
    }
}

// ============================================================
// Timestamped Event
// ============================================================

/// The type of event that occurred.
#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq, Eq)]
pub enum EventKind {
    Local(String),
    Send { to: u32, message: String },
    Receive { from: u32, message: String },
}

/// An event decorated with a Lamport timestamp.
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Eq, PartialEq)]
pub struct TimestampedEvent {
    pub timestamp: u64,
    pub process_id: u32,
    pub event: EventKind,
}

impl TimestampedEvent {
    pub fn new(timestamp: u64, process_id: u32, event: EventKind) -> Self {
        Self { timestamp, process_id, event }
    }
}

impl fmt::Display for TimestampedEvent {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter<'_>) -> fmt::Result {
        let kind = match &self.event {
            EventKind::Local(desc) => format!("LOCAL({})", desc),
            EventKind::Send { to, message } => format!("SEND(to=P{}, msg='{}')", to, message),
            EventKind::Receive { from, message } => format!("RECV(from=P{}, msg='{}')", from, message),
        };
        write!(f, "[T={:>4}, P{}] {}", self.timestamp, self.process_id, kind)
    }
}

/// Total ordering for Lamport events:
///   Primary key  – timestamp (lower = earlier)
///   Tiebreaker   – process_id (arbitrary but deterministic)
impl Ord for TimestampedEvent {
    fn cmp(&self, other: &Self) -> Ordering {
        // BinaryHeap is a max-heap; we want min-heap, so reverse.
        other.timestamp
            .cmp(&self.timestamp)
            .then(other.process_id.cmp(&self.process_id))
    }
}

impl PartialOrd for TimestampedEvent {
    fn partial_cmp(&self, other: &Self) -> Option<Ordering> {
        Some(self.cmp(other))
    }
}

// ============================================================
// Process Node
// ============================================================

/// A simulated distributed process that records its event history.
pub struct Process {
    pub id: u32,
    pub clock: LamportClock,
    pub history: Vec<TimestampedEvent>,
}

impl Process {
    pub fn new(id: u32) -> Self {
        Self {
            id,
            clock: LamportClock::new(id),
            history: Vec::new(),
        }
    }

    /// Perform a local event.
    pub fn local_event(&mut self, description: &str) -> u64 {
        let ts = self.clock.tick();
        self.history.push(TimestampedEvent::new(
            ts,
            self.id,
            EventKind::Local(description.to_string()),
        ));
        ts
    }

    /// Prepare a message to send (returns (timestamp, message)).
    pub fn prepare_send(&mut self, to: u32, message: &str) -> (u64, String) {
        let ts = self.clock.send();
        self.history.push(TimestampedEvent::new(
            ts,
            self.id,
            EventKind::Send { to, message: message.to_string() },
        ));
        (ts, message.to_string())
    }

    /// Process an incoming message with its attached Lamport timestamp.
    pub fn receive_message(&mut self, from: u32, message: &str, sender_timestamp: u64) -> u64 {
        let ts = self.clock.receive(sender_timestamp);
        self.history.push(TimestampedEvent::new(
            ts,
            self.id,
            EventKind::Receive { from, message: message.to_string() },
        ));
        ts
    }
}

// ============================================================
// Network / Message Bus
// ============================================================

/// An in-flight message carrying a Lamport timestamp.
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct Message {
    pub from: u32,
    pub to: u32,
    pub content: String,
    pub lamport_timestamp: u64,
}

/// A simple synchronous message bus for simulation purposes.
pub struct Network {
    pub processes: HashMap<u32, Process>,
    pub global_log: Vec<TimestampedEvent>,
}

impl Network {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self {
            processes: HashMap::new(),
            global_log: Vec::new(),
        }
    }

    pub fn add_process(&mut self, id: u32) {
        self.processes.insert(id, Process::new(id));
    }

    /// Deliver a message from `from` to `to` with an attached timestamp.
    pub fn send_message(&mut self, from: u32, to: u32, message: &str) {
        // Step 1: sender prepares send event
        let (ts, msg) = self
            .processes
            .get_mut(&from)
            .expect("sender not found")
            .prepare_send(to, message);

        // Step 2: receiver processes receive event
        self.processes
            .get_mut(&to)
            .expect("receiver not found")
            .receive_message(from, &msg, ts);
    }

    /// Trigger a local event on a process.
    pub fn local_event(&mut self, process_id: u32, description: &str) {
        self.processes
            .get_mut(&process_id)
            .expect("process not found")
            .local_event(description);
    }

    /// Collect all events from every process into a globally sorted log.
    pub fn build_global_log(&mut self) {
        let mut heap: BinaryHeap<TimestampedEvent> = BinaryHeap::new();
        for p in self.processes.values() {
            for event in &p.history {
                heap.push(event.clone());
            }
        }
        self.global_log.clear();
        while let Some(event) = heap.pop() {
            self.global_log.push(event);
        }
    }

    /// Print the history of a single process.
    pub fn print_process_history(&self, process_id: u32) {
        if let Some(p) = self.processes.get(&process_id) {
            println!("── Process {} history ──", process_id);
            for e in &p.history {
                println!("  {}", e);
            }
        }
    }

    /// Print the globally ordered event log.
    pub fn print_global_log(&self) {
        println!("── Global Total Order ──");
        for (i, e) in self.global_log.iter().enumerate() {
            println!("  {:>2}. {}", i + 1, e);
        }
    }
}

// ============================================================
// Happens-Before Checker
// ============================================================

/// Check whether event `a` happens-before event `b` under Lamport's definition.
/// Returns true when a.timestamp < b.timestamp, or timestamps are equal but
/// a.process_id < b.process_id (using our tiebreaker convention).
pub fn happens_before(a: &TimestampedEvent, b: &TimestampedEvent) -> bool {
    match a.timestamp.cmp(&b.timestamp) {
        Ordering::Less => true,
        Ordering::Greater => false,
        Ordering::Equal => a.process_id < b.process_id,
    }
}

/// Check whether two events are concurrent (neither happens-before the other).
pub fn concurrent(a: &TimestampedEvent, b: &TimestampedEvent) -> bool {
    !happens_before(a, b) && !happens_before(b, a)
}

