## Key Design Decisions

### Structure
| Component | Role |
|-----------|------|
| `Node<K,V>` | Stores key, value, and level-indexed forward pointers |
| `Header<K,V>` | Sentinel with only forward pointers (no key/value) |
| `SkipList<K,V>` | Owns the header, tracks current level and length |

### Why Raw Pointers?
Rust's borrow checker prevents self-referential structures that would be needed for a safe skip list. Raw pointers are the idiomatic solution here, with careful ownership management:
- `Box::new` allocates nodes on the heap
- `std::mem::forget` transfers ownership out of Rust's automatic management
- `Box::from_raw` reclaims ownership during removal/drop

### Algorithm Highlights
- **`random_level()`** — each level added with probability 0.5 (geometric distribution), capped at `MAX_LEVEL = 16`
- **`insert()`** — builds an `update[]` array of predecessor nodes at each level, splices new node in
- **`remove()`** — same traversal, unlinks the node, then reclaims memory with `Box::from_raw`
- **`iter()`** — follows level-0 links for O(n) in-order traversal

### Complexity
| Operation | Average | Worst |
|-----------|---------|-------|
| Insert | O(log n) | O(n) |
| Get | O(log n) | O(n) |
| Remove | O(log n) | O(n) |
| Iter | O(n) | O(n) |

# N-Queens Problem in Rust

## Overview
The N-Queens problem asks you to place N chess queens on an N×N chessboard so that no two queens threaten each other (no two queens share the same row, column, or diagonal).

## Implementation

```rust
fn solve_n_queens(n: usize) -> Vec<Vec<String>> {
    let mut solutions = Vec::new();
    let mut board = vec![0usize; n]; // board[row] = col position of queen in that row

    solve(&mut board, 0, n, &mut solutions);
    solutions
}

fn solve(
    board: &mut Vec<usize>,
    row: usize,
    n: usize,
    solutions: &mut Vec<Vec<String>>,
) {
    if row == n {
        solutions.push(format_board(board, n));
        return;
    }

    for col in 0..n {
        if is_safe(board, row, col) {
            board[row] = col;
            solve(board, row + 1, n, solutions);
        }
    }
}

fn is_safe(board: &[usize], row: usize, col: usize) -> bool {
    for prev_row in 0..row {
        let prev_col = board[prev_row];

        // Check same column
        if prev_col == col {
            return false;
        }

        // Check diagonals
        let row_diff = row - prev_row; // always positive since prev_row < row
        let col_diff = if col > prev_col {
            col - prev_col
        } else {
            prev_col - col
        };

        if row_diff == col_diff {
            return false;
        }
    }
    true
}

fn format_board(board: &[usize], n: usize) -> Vec<String> {
    board
        .iter()
        .map(|&col| {
            let mut row = String::with_capacity(n);
            for c in 0..n {
                if c == col {
                    row.push('Q');
                } else {
                    row.push('.');
                }
            }
            row
        })
        .collect()
}

fn print_solution(solution: &[String], index: usize) {
    println!("Solution {}:", index + 1);
    for row in solution {
        println!("  {}", row);
    }
    println!();
}

fn main() {
    for n in 1..=9 {
        let solutions = solve_n_queens(n);
        println!(
            "N={}: {} solution(s) found",
            n,
            solutions.len()
        );
    }

    println!("\n--- Detailed solutions for N=6 ---\n");
    let solutions = solve_n_queens(6);
    for (i, solution) in solutions.iter().enumerate() {
        print_solution(solution, i);
    }

    println!("--- First solution for N=8 ---\n");
    let solutions = solve_n_queens(8);
    println!("Total solutions for N=8: {}", solutions.len());
    if let Some(first) = solutions.first() {
        print_solution(first, 0);
    }
}
```

