# Prime Number Checker in Rust

## Implementation

```rust
fn is_prime(n: u64) -> bool {
    if n < 2 {
        return false;
    }
    if n == 2 {
        return true;
    }
    if n % 2 == 0 {
        return false;
    }
    if n == 3 {
        return true;
    }
    if n % 3 == 0 {
        return false;
    }

    // Check divisors of the form 6k ± 1 up to √n
    let mut i = 5u64;
    while i * i <= n {
        if n % i == 0 || n % (i + 2) == 0 {
            return false;
        }
        i += 6;
    }

    true
}

fn main() {
    let test_cases = vec![
        (0, false),
        (1, false),
        (2, true),
        (3, true),
        (4, false),
        (17, true),
        (25, false),
        (97, true),
        (100, false),
        (7919, true),        // 1000th prime
        (1_000_003, true),   // large prime
    ];

    println!("{:<12} {:<10} {:<10} {}", "Number", "Expected", "Got", "Status");
    println!("{}", "-".repeat(45));

    for (n, expected) in &test_cases {
        let result = is_prime(*n);
        let status = if result == *expected { "✓ PASS" } else { "✗ FAIL" };
        println!("{:<12} {:<10} {:<10} {}", n, expected, result, status);
    }
}
```

## How It Works

The algorithm uses several optimizations:

| Step | Check | Reason |
|------|-------|--------|
| 1 | `n < 2` → false | Primes are ≥ 2 |
| 2 | `n == 2` → true | 2 is the only even prime |
| 3 | `n % 2 == 0` → false | Eliminate all even numbers |
| 4 | `n == 3` → true | 3 is prime |
| 5 | `n % 3 == 0` → false | Eliminate multiples of 3 |
| 6 | Check `6k ± 1` up to `√n` | All primes > 3 have this form |

### The `6k ± 1` Optimization

Every integer can be expressed as one of: `6k, 6k+1, 6k+2, 6k+3, 6k+4, 6k+5`

- `6k`, `6k+2`, `6k+4` → divisible by 2
- `6k+3` → divisible by 3
- Only `6k+1` and `6k+5` (= `6k-1`) can be prime

This reduces trial divisions by ~**67%** compared to checking every number.

