## Key Design Decisions

| Decision | Reason |
|---|---|
| `&[T]` slice input | Works with arrays, `Vec`, and any contiguous memory |
| `T: Ord` bound | Enables `<`, `>`, `==` via `cmp` / `Ordering` |
| `low + (high - low) / 2` | Avoids integer overflow vs `(low + high) / 2` |
| `high = arr.len()` (exclusive) | Standard half-open interval `[low, high)` avoids off-by-one errors |
| Returns `Option<usize>` | Idiomatic Rust; no sentinel values like `-1` |
| Generic over `T` | Works with integers, floats (via `OrderedFloat`), strings, custom types |

# Flatten a Nested List in Rust

Here's a complete implementation that handles arbitrarily nested lists using a recursive enum type.

## Implementation

```rust
/// Represents a nested list that can contain either integers or other nested lists
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
enum NestedList {
    Int(i64),
    List(Vec<NestedList>),
}

/// Flattens a nested list into a flat vector of integers
fn flatten(nested: &NestedList) -> Vec<i64> {
    match nested {
        NestedList::Int(n) => vec![*n],
        NestedList::List(items) => items.iter().flat_map(flatten).collect(),
    }
}

/// Flattens a slice of nested lists into a flat vector of integers
fn flatten_list(nested: &[NestedList]) -> Vec<i64> {
    nested.iter().flat_map(flatten).collect()
}

fn main() {
    // Example 1: [[1, 2], [3, [4, 5]], 6]
    let nested = NestedList::List(vec![
        NestedList::List(vec![NestedList::Int(1), NestedList::Int(2)]),
        NestedList::List(vec![
            NestedList::Int(3),
            NestedList::List(vec![NestedList::Int(4), NestedList::Int(5)]),
        ]),
        NestedList::Int(6),
    ]);

    println!("Input:  {:?}", nested);
    println!("Output: {:?}", flatten(&nested));

    // Example 2: [1, [2, [3, [4, [5]]]]]
    let deeply_nested = NestedList::List(vec![
        NestedList::Int(1),
        NestedList::List(vec![
            NestedList::Int(2),
            NestedList::List(vec![
                NestedList::Int(3),
                NestedList::List(vec![
                    NestedList::Int(4),
                    NestedList::List(vec![NestedList::Int(5)]),
                ]),
            ]),
        ]),
    ]);

    println!("\nInput:  {:?}", deeply_nested);
    println!("Output: {:?}", flatten(&deeply_nested));

    // Example 3: Using flatten_list with a top-level Vec<NestedList>
    let items = vec![
        NestedList::Int(1),
        NestedList::List(vec![NestedList::Int(2), NestedList::Int(3)]),
        NestedList::List(vec![
            NestedList::List(vec![NestedList::Int(4)]),
            NestedList::Int(5),
        ]),
    ];

    println!("\nInput:  {:?}", items);
    println!("Output: {:?}", flatten_list(&items));

    // Example 4: Empty and single-element cases
    let empty = NestedList::List(vec![]);
    let single = NestedList::Int(42);

    println!("\nEmpty:  {:?}", flatten(&empty));
    println!("Single: {:?}", flatten(&single));
}

