## Design Notes

| Aspect | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Lookup** | O(1) via `HashMap<K, usize>` |
| **Insert/Evict** | O(1) linked list pointer manipulation |
| **Memory** | Arena-based node storage with a free-list for slot reuse |
| **Order tracking** | Doubly linked list (head = MRU, tail = LRU) |
| **Unsafe** | Used only in `remove`/`evict_lru` to move values out of the arena without cloning |

The key design decision is using **index-based pointers** (usize) into an arena `Vec` rather than raw pointers, which avoids most unsafe code while still achieving O(1) operations. The small amount of `unsafe` is isolated to value extraction from the arena when evicting or removing nodes.

# Binary Tree Serialization and Deserialization in Rust

## Overview

I'll implement serialization/deserialization using a pre-order traversal with null markers, similar to LeetCode's approach. The format will be a comma-separated string like `"1,2,4,#,#,5,#,#,3,#,#"`.

## Implementation

```rust
use std::collections::VecDeque;

// ── Tree Definition ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

#[derive(Debug, PartialEq, Clone)]
pub struct TreeNode {
    pub val: i32,
    pub left: Option<Box<TreeNode>>,
    pub right: Option<Box<TreeNode>>,
}

impl TreeNode {
    pub fn new(val: i32) -> Self {
        TreeNode { val, left: None, right: None }
    }

    /// Convenience builder so tests stay readable.
    pub fn with_children(
        val: i32,
        left: Option<Box<TreeNode>>,
        right: Option<Box<TreeNode>>,
    ) -> Box<Self> {
        Box::new(TreeNode { val, left, right })
    }
}

// ── Errors ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

#[derive(Debug, PartialEq)]
pub enum TreeError {
    InvalidFormat(String),
    ParseError(String),
}

impl std::fmt::Display for TreeError {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut std::fmt::Formatter<'_>) -> std::fmt::Result {
        match self {
            TreeError::InvalidFormat(msg) => write!(f, "Invalid format: {msg}"),
            TreeError::ParseError(msg)   => write!(f, "Parse error: {msg}"),
        }
    }
}

// ── Serialization ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

/// Serialize a binary tree to a compact string using pre-order traversal.
///
/// `None` nodes are represented by `"#"`.
/// Values are separated by `","`.
///
/// # Example
/// ```
/// //     1
/// //    / \
/// //   2   3
/// // Produces: "1,2,#,#,3,#,#"
/// ```
pub fn serialize(root: &Option<Box<TreeNode>>) -> String {
    let mut parts = Vec::new();
    serialize_helper(root, &mut parts);
    parts.join(",")
}

fn serialize_helper(node: &Option<Box<TreeNode>>, parts: &mut Vec<String>) {
    match node {
        None => parts.push("#".to_string()),
        Some(n) => {
            parts.push(n.val.to_string());
            serialize_helper(&n.left,  parts);
            serialize_helper(&n.right, parts);
        }
    }
}

// ── Deserialization ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

/// Deserialize a string produced by [`serialize`] back into a binary tree.
///
/// Returns `Ok(None)` for an empty / null tree and
/// `Err(TreeError)` when the input is malformed.
pub fn deserialize(data: &str) -> Result<Option<Box<TreeNode>>, TreeError> {
    if data.is_empty() {
        return Ok(None);
    }

    let tokens: Vec<&str> = data.split(',').collect();
    let mut iter = tokens.iter().peekable();
    deserialize_helper(&mut iter)
}

fn deserialize_helper<'a, I>(iter: &mut std::iter::Peekable<I>)
    -> Result<Option<Box<TreeNode>>, TreeError>
where
    I: Iterator<Item = &'a &'a str>,
{
    match iter.next() {
        None => Err(TreeError::InvalidFormat(
            "Unexpected end of token stream".to_string(),
        )),
        Some(&"#") => Ok(None),
        Some(&token) => {
            let val = token.parse::<i32>().map_err(|_| {
                TreeError::ParseError(format!("Cannot parse '{token}' as i32"))
            })?;

            let left  = deserialize_helper(iter)?;
            let right = deserialize_helper(iter)?;

            Ok(Some(Box::new(TreeNode { val, left, right })))
        }
    }
}

// ── Level-order (BFS) alternative ─────────────────────────────────────────────

/// Serialize using BFS (level-order), matching the LeetCode bracket notation.
///
/// Produces `"[1,2,3,#,#,4,5]"`.
pub fn serialize_bfs(root: &Option<Box<TreeNode>>) -> String {
    let mut result = Vec::new();
    let mut queue: VecDeque<Option<&Box<TreeNode>>> = VecDeque::new();

    match root {
        None => return "[]".to_string(),
        Some(node) => queue.push_back(Some(node)),
    }

    while let Some(current) = queue.pop_front() {
        match current {
            None => result.push("#".to_string()),
            Some(node) => {
                result.push(node.val.to_string());
                queue.push_back(node.left.as_ref());
                queue.push_back(node.right.as_ref());
            }
        }
    }

    // Trim trailing nulls for a cleaner output.
    while result.last().map(|s| s.as_str()) == Some("#") {
        result.pop();
    }

    format!("[{}]", result.join(","))
}

/// Deserialize a BFS-format string `"[1,2,3,#,#,4,5]"`.
pub fn deserialize_bfs(data: &str) -> Result<Option<Box<TreeNode>>, TreeError> {
    let data = data.trim();
    if data == "[]" || data.is_empty() {
        return Ok(None);
    }

    // Strip surrounding brackets.
    let inner = data
        .strip_prefix('[')
        .and_then(|s| s.strip_suffix(']'))
        .ok_or_else(|| TreeError::InvalidFormat("Missing '[' or ']'".to_string()))?;

    let tokens: Vec<&str> = inner.split(',').collect();
    if tokens.is_empty() || tokens[0] == "#" {
        return Ok(None);
    }

    let root_val = tokens[0].parse::<i32>().map_err(|_| {
        TreeError::ParseError(format!("Cannot parse '{}' as i32", tokens[0]))
    })?;

    let root = Box::new(TreeNode::new(root_val));
    let mut queue: VecDeque<*mut TreeNode> = VecDeque::new();
    // SAFETY: root is alive for the duration of the loop below.
    queue.push_back(Box::into_raw(root));

    let mut i = 1;
    let mut roots: Vec<Box<TreeNode>> = Vec::new();

    // We keep a raw-pointer queue so we can mutate children while holding the
    // tree in a local Vec.  All allocations end up owned by `roots` or by the
    // single root node we return.
    let first_raw = *queue.front().unwrap();
    roots.push(unsafe { Box::from_raw(first_raw) });
    // Put it back – we'll take ownership at the end.
    let final_raw = Box::into_raw(roots.pop().unwrap());
    queue.clear();
    queue.push_back(final_raw);

    // Rebuild the tree iteratively.
    // We use a raw pointer queue to avoid fighting the borrow checker while
    // we append children.  All memory is tracked through the tree itself.
    while let Some(node_ptr) = queue.pop_front() {
        // Left child
        if i < tokens.len() {
            if tokens[i] != "#" {
                let val = tokens[i].parse::<i32>().map_err(|_| {
                    TreeError::ParseError(format!("Cannot parse '{}' as i32", tokens[i]))
                })?;
                let child = Box::new(TreeNode::new(val));
                let child_ptr = Box::into_raw(child);
                // SAFETY: node_ptr is valid; we own the tree.
                unsafe { (*node_ptr).left = Some(Box::from_raw(child_ptr)); }
                // Re-extract the raw pointer for the queue.
                let child_ref = unsafe {
                    (*node_ptr).left.as_mut().unwrap().as_mut() as *mut TreeNode
                };
                queue.push_back(child_ref);
            }
            i += 1;
        }

        // Right child
        if i < tokens.len() {
            if tokens[i] != "#" {
                let val = tokens[i].parse::<i32>().map_err(|_| {
                    TreeError::ParseError(format!("Cannot parse '{}' as i32", tokens[i]))
                })?;
                let child = Box::new(TreeNode::new(val));
                let child_ptr = Box::into_raw(child);
                unsafe { (*node_ptr).right = Some(Box::from_raw(child_ptr)); }
                let child_ref = unsafe {
                    (*node_ptr).right.as_mut().unwrap().as_mut() as *mut TreeNode
                };
                queue.push_back(child_ref);
            }
            i += 1;
        }
    }

    // SAFETY: final_raw was allocated by Box::new; we've been tracking it.
    Ok(Some(unsafe { Box::from_raw(final_raw) }))
}

// ── Helpers ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

/// Collect an in-order traversal for easy comparison in tests.
pub fn inorder(root: &Option<Box<TreeNode>>) -> Vec<i32> {
    let mut result = Vec::new();
    inorder_helper(root, &mut result);
    result
}

fn inorder_helper(node: &Option<Box<TreeNode>>, result: &mut Vec<i32>) {
    if let Some(n) = node {
        inorder_helper(&n.left,  result);
        result.push(n.val);
        inorder_helper(&n.right, result);
    }
}

