## How It Works

### DFS (Pre-order) Strategy

| Node | Token emitted |
|------|--------------|
| `Some(n)` | `n.val`, then recurse left, then recurse right |
| `None` | `#` |

Deserialization consumes tokens from a shared iterator in the same pre-order, reconstructing children recursively.

### BFS (Level-order) Strategy

Serialization uses a **queue** to emit values level by level, appending `#` for null children. Trailing nulls are stripped. Deserialization rebuilds nodes via a queue of raw pointers to parent nodes, assigning children as tokens are consumed.

## Sample Output

```
=== Pre-order (DFS) serialization ===
Serialized : 1,2,4,#,#,5,#,#,3,#,#
Round-trip : ✓ OK
In-order   : [4, 2, 5, 1, 3]

=== BFS (level-order) serialization ===
Serialized : [1,2,3,4,5]
Round-trip : ✓ OK
In-order   : [4, 2, 5, 1, 3]

=== Edge cases ===
Empty tree  DFS: #
Empty tree  BFS: []
Single node DFS: 42,#,#
Single node BFS: [42]
```

# Trie Data Structure in Rust

## Overview

A Trie (prefix tree) is a tree-like data structure used to store strings where each node represents a character. This implementation supports insert, search, starts_with (prefix search), and delete operations.

## Implementation

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;

/// A node in the Trie
#[derive(Debug, Default)]
struct TrieNode {
    children: HashMap<char, TrieNode>,
    is_end_of_word: bool,
    count: usize, // Number of words passing through this node
}

impl TrieNode {
    fn new() -> Self {
        TrieNode {
            children: HashMap::new(),
            is_end_of_word: false,
            count: 0,
        }
    }
}

/// Trie data structure
#[derive(Debug, Default)]
pub struct Trie {
    root: TrieNode,
    word_count: usize,
}

impl Trie {
    /// Creates a new empty Trie
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Trie {
            root: TrieNode::new(),
            word_count: 0,
        }
    }

    /// Inserts a word into the Trie
    /// Returns true if the word was newly inserted, false if it already existed
    pub fn insert(&mut self, word: &str) -> bool {
        let mut current = &mut self.root;

        for ch in word.chars() {
            current.count += 1;
            current = current.children.entry(ch).or_insert_with(TrieNode::new);
        }

        if current.is_end_of_word {
            return false; // Word already exists
        }

        current.count += 1;
        current.is_end_of_word = true;
        self.word_count += 1;
        true
    }

    /// Searches for an exact word in the Trie
    /// Returns true if the word exists
    pub fn search(&self, word: &str) -> bool {
        self.find_node(word)
            .map(|node| node.is_end_of_word)
            .unwrap_or(false)
    }

    /// Returns true if any word in the Trie starts with the given prefix
    pub fn starts_with(&self, prefix: &str) -> bool {
        self.find_node(prefix).is_some()
    }

    /// Returns all words in the Trie that start with the given prefix
    pub fn words_with_prefix(&self, prefix: &str) -> Vec<String> {
        let mut results = Vec::new();

        if let Some(node) = self.find_node(prefix) {
            let mut current_word = prefix.to_string();
            self.collect_words(node, &mut current_word, &mut results);
        }

        results
    }

    /// Returns all words stored in the Trie
    pub fn all_words(&self) -> Vec<String> {
        self.words_with_prefix("")
    }

    /// Deletes a word from the Trie
    /// Returns true if the word was found and deleted, false if it didn't exist
    pub fn delete(&mut self, word: &str) -> bool {
        if !self.search(word) {
            return false;
        }

        self.word_count -= 1;
        Self::delete_recursive(&mut self.root, word, 0);
        true
    }

    /// Returns the number of words in the Trie
    pub fn word_count(&self) -> usize {
        self.word_count
    }

    /// Returns true if the Trie is empty
    pub fn is_empty(&self) -> bool {
        self.word_count == 0
    }

    /// Returns the number of words that start with the given prefix
    pub fn count_words_with_prefix(&self, prefix: &str) -> usize {
        self.find_node(prefix)
            .map(|node| node.count)
            .unwrap_or(0)
    }

    /// Clears all words from the Trie
    pub fn clear(&mut self) {
        self.root = TrieNode::new();
        self.word_count = 0;
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------
    // Private helpers
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------------

    /// Traverses the Trie following the given string and returns the final node
    fn find_node(&self, s: &str) -> Option<&TrieNode> {
        let mut current = &self.root;

        for ch in s.chars() {
            match current.children.get(&ch) {
                Some(node) => current = node,
                None => return None,
            }
        }

        Some(current)
    }

    /// Recursively collects all words from a given node
    fn collect_words(&self, node: &TrieNode, current_word: &mut String, results: &mut Vec<String>) {
        if node.is_end_of_word {
            results.push(current_word.clone());
        }

        // Sort children for deterministic output
        let mut children: Vec<(&char, &TrieNode)> = node.children.iter().collect();
        children.sort_by_key(|&(ch, _)| ch);

        for (ch, child) in children {
            current_word.push(*ch);
            self.collect_words(child, current_word, results);
            current_word.pop();
        }
    }

    /// Recursively deletes a word, pruning empty branches
    /// Returns true if the current node should be removed
    fn delete_recursive(node: &mut TrieNode, word: &str, depth: usize) -> bool {
        let chars: Vec<char> = word.chars().collect();

        if depth == chars.len() {
            node.is_end_of_word = false;
            node.count -= 1;
            return node.children.is_empty();
        }

        let ch = chars[depth];

        if let Some(child) = node.children.get_mut(&ch) {
            child.count -= 1;
            let should_delete_child = Self::delete_recursive(child, word, depth + 1);

            if should_delete_child {
                node.children.remove(&ch);
            }
        }

        // Remove this node if it has no children and is not the end of another word
        !node.is_end_of_word && node.children.is_empty()
    }
}

