## Key Design Decisions

| Decision | Rationale |
|---|---|
| `HashMap<char, TrieNode>` for children | Handles Unicode naturally; memory-efficient for sparse alphabets |
| `count` per node | Enables O(prefix_len) prefix-count queries without traversal |
| Recursive delete with pruning | Removes empty branches to keep memory tidy |
| Returns `bool` from `insert`/`delete` | Lets callers know if the operation changed state |
| Sorted output in `collect_words` | Deterministic results without requiring a sorted structure |

## Complexity

| Operation | Time | Space |
|---|---|---|
| `insert` | O(m) | O(m) |
| `search` | O(m) | O(1) |
| `starts_with` | O(m) | O(1) |
| `delete` | O(m) | O(1) |
| `words_with_prefix` | O(m + k) | O(k) |
| `count_words_with_prefix` | O(m) | O(1) |

*m = word/prefix length, k = total characters in matching words*

# Permutations in Rust

Here's a complete implementation that generates all permutations of a list using Heap's algorithm and a recursive approach.

```rust
fn permutations<T: Clone>(items: &[T]) -> Vec<Vec<T>> {
    if items.is_empty() {
        return vec![vec![]];
    }

    let mut result = Vec::new();
    permute_recursive(items.to_vec(), 0, &mut result);
    result
}

fn permute_recursive<T: Clone>(mut items: Vec<T>, start: usize, result: &mut Vec<Vec<T>>) {
    if start == items.len() {
        result.push(items.clone());
        return;
    }

    for i in start..items.len() {
        items.swap(start, i);
        permute_recursive(items.clone(), start + 1, result);
        items.swap(start, i); // backtrack
    }
}

/// Alternative: Heap's Algorithm (iterative)
fn permutations_heap<T: Clone>(items: &[T]) -> Vec<Vec<T>> {
    let n = items.len();
    let mut items = items.to_vec();
    let mut result = Vec::new();
    let mut c = vec![0usize; n];

    result.push(items.clone());

    let mut i = 0;
    while i < n {
        if c[i] < i {
            if i % 2 == 0 {
                items.swap(0, i);
            } else {
                items.swap(c[i], i);
            }
            result.push(items.clone());
            c[i] += 1;
            i = 0;
        } else {
            c[i] = 0;
            i += 1;
        }
    }

    result
}

/// Iterator-based approach for memory efficiency
struct Permutations<T: Clone> {
    items: Vec<T>,
    indices: Vec<usize>,
    cycles: Vec<usize>,
    first: bool,
}

impl<T: Clone> Permutations<T> {
    fn new(items: Vec<T>) -> Self {
        let n = items.len();
        let cycles: Vec<usize> = (1..=n).rev().collect();
        let indices: Vec<usize> = (0..n).collect();
        Permutations {
            items,
            indices,
            cycles,
            first: true,
        }
    }
}

impl<T: Clone> Iterator for Permutations<T> {
    type Item = Vec<T>;

    fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item> {
        let n = self.items.len();

        if n == 0 {
            return if self.first {
                self.first = false;
                Some(vec![])
            } else {
                None
            };
        }

        if self.first {
            self.first = false;
            return Some(self.indices.iter().map(|&i| self.items[i].clone()).collect());
        }

        for i in (0..n).rev() {
            self.cycles[i] -= 1;
            if self.cycles[i] == 0 {
                // Rotate indices[i..] left by 1
                let tmp = self.indices[i];
                for j in i..n - 1 {
                    self.indices[j] = self.indices[j + 1];
                }
                self.indices[n - 1] = tmp;
                self.cycles[i] = n - i;
            } else {
                let j = n - self.cycles[i];
                self.indices.swap(i, j);
                return Some(self.indices.iter().map(|&idx| self.items[idx].clone()).collect());
            }
        }

        None
    }
}

fn main() {
    // --- Recursive approach ---
    println!("=== Recursive Permutations ===");
    let numbers = vec![1, 2, 3];
    let perms = permutations(&numbers);
    println!("Permutations of {:?} ({} total):", numbers, perms.len());
    for p in &perms {
        println!("  {:?}", p);
    }

    // --- Heap's Algorithm ---
    println!("\n=== Heap's Algorithm ===");
    let chars = vec!['a', 'b', 'c'];
    let perms_heap = permutations_heap(&chars);
    println!("Permutations of {:?} ({} total):", chars, perms_heap.len());
    for p in &perms_heap {
        println!("  {:?}", p);
    }

    // --- Iterator approach ---
    println!("\n=== Iterator-based Permutations ===");
    let words = vec!["foo", "bar", "baz"];
    let perm_iter = Permutations::new(words.clone());
    let collected: Vec<_> = perm_iter.collect();
    println!("Permutations of {:?} ({} total):", words, collected.len());
    for p in &collected {
        println!("  {:?}", p);
    }

    // --- Edge cases ---
    println!("\n=== Edge Cases ===");
    let empty: Vec<i32> = vec![];
    println!("Permutations of [] : {:?}", permutations(&empty));

    let single = vec![42];
    println!("Permutations of [42]: {:?}", permutations(&single));

    // --- Count verification ---
    println!("\n=== Count Verification ===");
    for n in 0..=5 {
        let input: Vec<usize> = (1..=n).collect();
        let count = permutations(&input).len();
        let factorial: usize = (1..=n).product::<usize>().max(1);
        println!("n={}: {} permutations ({}! = {})", n, count, n, factorial);
    }
}
