## Key Concepts

| Component | Description |
|-----------|-------------|
| **DP Table** | `dp[i][j]` stores LCS length of first `i` chars of s1 and first `j` chars of s2 |
| **Recurrence** | If `s1[i] == s2[j]`: `dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1`, else `max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])` |
| **Backtracking** | Reconstruct the actual subsequence by walking back through the DP table |
| **Time Complexity** | O(m × n) where m, n are string lengths |
| **Space Complexity** | O(m × n) for full table; O(n) for length-only version |

# Lock-Free Stack in Rust Using Atomics

## Overview

This implementation uses a **Treiber stack** — the classic lock-free stack algorithm based on atomic compare-and-swap operations. It handles the ABA problem using a generation counter (tagged pointers).

## Implementation

```rust
use std::sync::atomic::{AtomicUsize, Ordering};
use std::ptr;
use std::mem::ManuallyDrop;

/// A node in the lock-free stack.
struct Node<T> {
    data: ManuallyDrop<T>,
    next: *mut Node<T>,
    /// Generation counter to help mitigate ABA problem.
    generation: usize,
}

/// A tagged pointer packing a raw pointer and a generation counter.
/// Uses the lower bits for the tag on 64-bit systems where pointers
/// are aligned (we store tag separately via AtomicTaggedPtr instead).
#[derive(Clone, Copy)]
struct TaggedPtr {
    ptr: usize,  // raw pointer as usize
    tag: usize,  // generation tag
}

/// Atomic tagged pointer using two separate AtomicUsize values.
struct AtomicTaggedPtr {
    ptr: AtomicUsize,
    tag: AtomicUsize,
}

impl AtomicTaggedPtr {
    const fn new(ptr: usize, tag: usize) -> Self {
        Self {
            ptr: AtomicUsize::new(ptr),
            tag: AtomicUsize::new(tag),
        }
    }

    /// Loads both fields. Not atomically consistent across both words,
    /// but we validate in CAS so this is safe for our use case.
    fn load(&self, order: Ordering) -> TaggedPtr {
        TaggedPtr {
            ptr: self.ptr.load(order),
            tag: self.tag.load(order),
        }
    }

    /// Compare-and-swap: only succeeds if both ptr and tag match.
    fn compare_exchange(
        &self,
        current: TaggedPtr,
        new: TaggedPtr,
        success: Ordering,
        failure: Ordering,
    ) -> Result<TaggedPtr, TaggedPtr> {
        // We use a double-width CAS simulation:
        // First attempt to CAS the tag, then the pointer.
        // If tag CAS fails, the operation failed.
        match self.tag.compare_exchange(current.tag, new.tag, success, failure) {
            Ok(_) => {
                match self.ptr.compare_exchange(current.ptr, new.ptr, success, failure) {
                    Ok(_) => Ok(new),
                    Err(actual_ptr) => {
                        // Undo tag change
                        self.tag.store(current.tag, Ordering::Release);
                        Err(TaggedPtr { ptr: actual_ptr, tag: current.tag })
                    }
                }
            }
            Err(actual_tag) => Err(TaggedPtr {
                ptr: self.ptr.load(failure),
                tag: actual_tag,
            }),
        }
    }
}

/// A lock-free stack safe for concurrent use.
///
/// # Safety & Correctness
/// - Uses tagged pointers (generation counters) to mitigate ABA.
/// - Memory reclamation is deferred until the stack is dropped.
///   For production use, consider epoch-based reclamation (e.g., `crossbeam-epoch`).
pub struct LockFreeStack<T> {
    head: AtomicTaggedPtr,
    /// Global generation counter incremented on each push.
    global_gen: AtomicUsize,
    /// Track node count for diagnostics.
    len: AtomicUsize,
}

// SAFETY: The stack uses raw pointers but we ensure exclusive access through
// atomic operations. T must be Send for cross-thread data movement.
unsafe impl<T: Send> Send for LockFreeStack<T> {}
unsafe impl<T: Send> Sync for LockFreeStack<T> {}

impl<T> LockFreeStack<T> {
    /// Creates a new empty lock-free stack.
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self {
            head: AtomicTaggedPtr::new(0, 0),
            global_gen: AtomicUsize::new(1),
            len: AtomicUsize::new(0),
        }
    }

    /// Returns the number of elements currently in the stack.
    /// Note: This is an approximate count under concurrent use.
    pub fn len(&self) -> usize {
        self.len.load(Ordering::Relaxed)
    }

    /// Returns true if the stack is empty.
    pub fn is_empty(&self) -> bool {
        self.head.ptr.load(Ordering::Acquire) == 0
    }

    /// Pushes a value onto the top of the stack.
    ///
    /// This operation is wait-free from the perspective of each thread
    /// making progress (CAS retry loop is lock-free overall).
    pub fn push(&self, value: T) {
        let gen = self.global_gen.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed);

        // Allocate a new node on the heap.
        let node = Box::into_raw(Box::new(Node {
            data: ManuallyDrop::new(value),
            next: ptr::null_mut(),
            generation: gen,
        }));

        loop {
            // Read the current head.
            let current_head = self.head.load(Ordering::Acquire);
            let current_ptr = current_head.ptr as *mut Node<T>;

            // Link our new node to the current head.
            unsafe { (*node).next = current_ptr; }

            let new_head = TaggedPtr {
                ptr: node as usize,
                tag: gen,
            };

            // Attempt to swing the head pointer to our new node.
            match self.head.compare_exchange(
                current_head,
                new_head,
                Ordering::Release,
                Ordering::Relaxed,
            ) {
                Ok(_) => {
                    self.len.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed);
                    return;
                }
                Err(_) => {
                    // Another thread modified the head; retry.
                    std::hint::spin_loop();
                }
            }
        }
    }

    /// Pops a value from the top of the stack.
    ///
    /// Returns `None` if the stack is empty.
    pub fn pop(&self) -> Option<T> {
        loop {
            let current_head = self.head.load(Ordering::Acquire);
            let current_ptr = current_head.ptr as *mut Node<T>;

            // Stack is empty.
            if current_ptr.is_null() {
                return None;
            }

            // SAFETY: current_ptr was a valid Box<Node<T>> when pushed,
            // and we haven't freed it yet (no memory reclamation in flight).
            let next_ptr = unsafe { (*current_ptr).next };

            let new_head = TaggedPtr {
                ptr: next_ptr as usize,
                // Use a fresh tag to distinguish this pop from any future push.
                tag: self.global_gen.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed),
            };

            // Attempt to swing head to the next node.
            match self.head.compare_exchange(
                current_head,
                new_head,
                Ordering::Release,
                Ordering::Acquire,
            ) {
                Ok(_) => {
                    self.len.fetch_sub(1, Ordering::Relaxed);
                    // SAFETY: We successfully removed this node; we now own it.
                    unsafe {
                        let data = ManuallyDrop::take(&mut (*current_ptr).data);
                        // Deallocate the node without running T's destructor
                        // (we already moved data out).
                        drop(Box::from_raw(current_ptr));
                        return Some(data);
                    }
                }
                Err(_) => {
                    // Another thread modified the head; retry.
                    std::hint::spin_loop();
                }
            }
        }
    }

    /// Peeks at the top element without removing it.
    ///
    /// # Safety
    /// The returned reference may be invalidated if another thread pops
    /// the element concurrently. Use with care in concurrent contexts.
    /// Prefer `pop()` for safe concurrent access.
    pub fn peek(&self) -> Option<&T> {
        let head_ptr = self.head.ptr.load(Ordering::Acquire) as *mut Node<T>;
        if head_ptr.is_null() {
            None
        } else {
            // SAFETY: If head_ptr is non-null, it points to a valid Node<T>
            // that hasn't been freed yet (no concurrent free possible here
            // since we hold no lock — caller must ensure stability).
            unsafe { Some(&(*head_ptr).data) }
        }
    }
}

impl<T> Drop for LockFreeStack<T> {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        // Drain all remaining elements to run their destructors.
        while self.pop().is_some() {}
    }
}

impl<T> Default for LockFreeStack<T> {
    fn default() -> Self {
        Self::new()
    }
}

// ============================================================
// Iterator support
// ============================================================

pub struct IntoIter<T>(LockFreeStack<T>);

impl<T> Iterator for IntoIter<T> {
    type Item = T;

    fn next(&mut self) -> Option<T> {
        self.0.pop()
    }
}

impl<T> IntoIterator for LockFreeStack<T> {
    type Item = T;
    type IntoIter = IntoIter<T>;

    fn into_iter(self) -> Self::IntoIter {
        IntoIter(self)
    }
}

