## Key Design Decisions

### Treiber Stack Algorithm
```
Push:                          Pop:
  node.next = head               if head == null: return None
  if CAS(&head, old, node)       next = head.next
    return                       if CAS(&head, head, next)
  else retry                       return head.data
                                 else retry
```

### ABA Problem Mitigation

| Approach | This Implementation |
|----------|-------------------|
| Problem | Thread reads head=A, sleeps; A popped, B pushed, A pushed again; CAS succeeds incorrectly |
| Solution | Generation counter — even if pointer is same, tag differs |
| Trade-off | Two-word CAS isn't truly atomic (hardware `DCAS` not available in stable Rust) |

### Memory Ordering Strategy

| Operation | Ordering | Reason |
|-----------|----------|--------|
| `push` CAS success | `Release` | Publishes node data to other threads |
| `pop` CAS load | `Acquire` | Sees all writes before the push |
| `pop` CAS success | `Release/Acquire` | Synchronizes removal |
| `len` / `gen` | `Relaxed` | Approximate counters, no sync needed |

### Production Considerations

- **Memory Reclamation**: Use `crossbeam-epoch` or hazard pointers to safely free nodes without use-after-free in highly concurrent scenarios
- **True DCAS**: Use `crossbeam-utils::AtomicCell` or platform intrinsics for genuine double-word CAS
- **Backoff**: Add exponential backoff in retry loops under high contention

# B-Tree Implementation in Rust

## Overview

This implementation provides a complete B-tree with insertion, search, deletion, and traversal operations. A B-tree of order `t` (minimum degree) maintains:
- Every node has at most `2t - 1` keys
- Every non-root node has at least `t - 1` keys
- All leaves are at the same depth

## Implementation

```rust
use std::fmt::Debug;

const MIN_DEGREE: usize = 3; // Minimum degree t (order 2t-1 = 5 keys max per node)

/// A node in the B-tree
#[derive(Debug)]
struct BTreeNode<K: Ord + Debug + Clone, V: Debug + Clone> {
    keys: Vec<K>,
    values: Vec<V>,
    children: Vec<BTreeNode<K, V>>,
    leaf: bool,
}

impl<K: Ord + Debug + Clone, V: Debug + Clone> BTreeNode<K, V> {
    fn new(leaf: bool) -> Self {
        BTreeNode {
            keys: Vec::new(),
            values: Vec::new(),
            children: Vec::new(),
            leaf,
        }
    }

    fn is_full(&self) -> bool {
        self.keys.len() == 2 * MIN_DEGREE - 1
    }

    /// Search for a key in the subtree rooted at this node.
    /// Returns Some(&V) if found, None otherwise.
    fn search(&self, key: &K) -> Option<&V> {
        let mut i = 0;
        while i < self.keys.len() && key > &self.keys[i] {
            i += 1;
        }

        if i < self.keys.len() && key == &self.keys[i] {
            Some(&self.values[i])
        } else if self.leaf {
            None
        } else {
            self.children[i].search(key)
        }
    }

    /// Insert a key-value pair into a node that is NOT full.
    fn insert_non_full(&mut self, key: K, value: V) {
        let mut i = self.keys.len();

        if self.leaf {
            // Find position and insert
            while i > 0 && key < self.keys[i - 1] {
                i -= 1;
            }
            // Update if key already exists
            if i < self.keys.len() && self.keys[i] == key {
                self.values[i] = value;
                return;
            }
            self.keys.insert(i, key);
            self.values.insert(i, value);
        } else {
            // Find child to descend into
            while i > 0 && key < self.keys[i - 1] {
                i -= 1;
            }
            // Update if key already exists in this node
            if i < self.keys.len() && self.keys[i] == key {
                self.values[i] = value;
                return;
            }

            // Split child if full before descending
            if self.children[i].is_full() {
                self.split_child(i);
                // After split, determine which of the two children to descend
                if key > self.keys[i] {
                    i += 1;
                } else if key == self.keys[i] {
                    // Key was promoted to this node
                    self.values[i] = value;
                    return;
                }
            }
            self.children[i].insert_non_full(key, value);
        }
    }

    /// Split the i-th child of this node (which must be full).
    /// This node must NOT be full.
    fn split_child(&mut self, i: usize) {
        let t = MIN_DEGREE;
        // The median key index in the full child
        let mid = t - 1;

        // Take out the full child temporarily
        let mut full_child = self.children.remove(i);

        // Create new right child from the upper half of full_child
        let mut new_child = BTreeNode::new(full_child.leaf);
        new_child.keys = full_child.keys.split_off(mid + 1);
        new_child.values = full_child.values.split_off(mid + 1);

        if !full_child.leaf {
            new_child.children = full_child.children.split_off(mid + 1);
        }

        // Extract the median key/value
        let median_key = full_child.keys.pop().unwrap();
        let median_value = full_child.values.pop().unwrap();

        // Re-insert the (now smaller) left child and insert the new right child
        self.children.insert(i, full_child);
        self.children.insert(i + 1, new_child);

        // Promote the median to this node
        self.keys.insert(i, median_key);
        self.values.insert(i, median_value);
    }

    /// Returns the index of the first key >= `key`.
    fn find_key_index(&self, key: &K) -> usize {
        self.keys.partition_point(|k| k < key)
    }

    /// Delete a key from the subtree rooted at this node.
    fn delete(&mut self, key: &K) {
        let t = MIN_DEGREE;
        let i = self.find_key_index(key);

        if i < self.keys.len() && &self.keys[i] == key {
            // Key is present in this node
            if self.leaf {
                // Case 1: Simply remove from leaf
                self.keys.remove(i);
                self.values.remove(i);
            } else {
                self.delete_internal(i);
            }
        } else if !self.leaf {
            // Key is not in this node; descend into child[i]
            // Ensure child[i] has at least t keys before descending
            if self.children[i].keys.len() < t {
                self.fill_child(i);
                // After fill, the key may have moved; re-search
                self.delete(key);
            } else {
                self.children[i].delete(key);
            }
        }
        // If leaf and key not found, key doesn't exist in tree — no-op
    }

    /// Delete key at index `i` from an internal node.
    fn delete_internal(&mut self, i: usize) {
        let t = MIN_DEGREE;
        let key = &self.keys[i].clone();

        if self.children[i].keys.len() >= t {
            // Case 2a: Left child has >= t keys — replace with predecessor
            let (pred_key, pred_val) = self.children[i].get_predecessor();
            self.keys[i] = pred_key.clone();
            self.values[i] = pred_val;
            self.children[i].delete(&pred_key);
        } else if self.children[i + 1].keys.len() >= t {
            // Case 2b: Right child has >= t keys — replace with successor
            let (succ_key, succ_val) = self.children[i + 1].get_successor();
            self.keys[i] = succ_key.clone();
            self.values[i] = succ_val;
            self.children[i + 1].delete(&succ_key);
        } else {
            // Case 2c: Both children have t-1 keys — merge them
            self.merge_children(i);
            self.children[i].delete(key);
        }
    }

    /// Get the predecessor (rightmost key) of the subtree rooted at this node.
    fn get_predecessor(&self) -> (K, V) {
        if self.leaf {
            let last = self.keys.len() - 1;
            (self.keys[last].clone(), self.values[last].clone())
        } else {
            self.children.last().unwrap().get_predecessor()
        }
    }

    /// Get the successor (leftmost key) of the subtree rooted at this node.
    fn get_successor(&self) -> (K, V) {
        if self.leaf {
            (self.keys[0].clone(), self.values[0].clone())
        } else {
            self.children[0].get_successor()
        }
    }

    /// Ensure child at index `i` has at least `t` keys.
    fn fill_child(&mut self, i: usize) {
        let t = MIN_DEGREE;

        let left_has_extra = i > 0 && self.children[i - 1].keys.len() >= t;
        let right_has_extra =
            i + 1 < self.children.len() && self.children[i + 1].keys.len() >= t;

        if left_has_extra {
            self.borrow_from_left(i);
        } else if right_has_extra {
            self.borrow_from_right(i);
        } else if i + 1 < self.children.len() {
            self.merge_children(i);
        } else {
            // i is the last child, merge with left sibling
            self.merge_children(i - 1);
        }
    }

    /// Borrow a key from child[i-1] (left sibling) and give it to child[i].
    fn borrow_from_left(&mut self, i: usize) {
        // Move parent's key[i-1] down to child[i]'s front
        let parent_key = self.keys.remove(i - 1);
        let parent_val = self.values.remove(i - 1);
        self.children[i].keys.insert(0, parent_key);
        self.children[i].values.insert(0, parent_val);

        // Move left sibling's last key up to parent
        let sib = &mut self.children[i - 1];
        let sib_key = sib.keys.pop().unwrap();
        let sib_val = sib.values.pop().unwrap();

        // Move last child of left sibling to front of child[i] if not leaf
        if !sib.leaf {
            let sib_last_child = sib.children.pop().unwrap();
            self.children[i].children.insert(0, sib_last_child);
        }

        self.keys.insert(i - 1, sib_key);
        self.values.insert(i - 1, sib_val);
    }

    /// Borrow a key from child[i+1] (right sibling) and give it to child[i].
    fn borrow_from_right(&mut self, i: usize) {
        // Move parent's key[i] down to child[i]'s end
        let parent_key = self.keys.remove(i);
        let parent_val = self.values.remove(i);
        self.children[i].keys.push(parent_key);
        self.children[i].values.push(parent_val);

        // Move right sibling's first key up to parent
        let sib = &mut self.children[i + 1];
        let sib_key = sib.keys.remove(0);
        let sib_val = sib.values.remove(0);

        // Move first child of right sibling to end of child[i] if not leaf
        if !sib.leaf {
            let sib_first_child = sib.children.remove(0);
            self.children[i].children.push(sib_first_child);
        }

        self.keys.insert(i, sib_key);
        self.values.insert(i, sib_val);
    }

    /// Merge child[i+1] into child[i], pulling down parent key[i].
    fn merge_children(&mut self, i: usize) {
        let parent_key = self.keys.remove(i);
        let parent_val = self.values.remove(i);

        let right_child = self.children.remove(i + 1);

        let left_child = &mut self.children[i];
        left_child.keys.push(parent_key);
        left_child.values.push(parent_val);
        left_child.keys.extend(right_child.keys);
        left_child.values.extend(right_child.values);
        left_child.children.extend(right_child.children);
    }

    /// In-order traversal — yields (key, value) pairs in sorted order.
    fn traverse(&self, result: &mut Vec<(K, V)>) {
        for i in 0..self.keys.len() {
            if !self.leaf {
                self.children[i].traverse(result);
            }
            result.push((self.keys[i].clone(), self.values[i].clone()));
        }
        if !self.leaf {
            self.children[self.keys.len()].traverse(result);
        }
    }

    /// Pretty-print the tree structure.
    fn print_tree(&self, depth: usize) {
        let indent = "  ".repeat(depth);
        let keys: Vec<_> = self
            .keys
            .iter()
            .zip(self.values.iter())
            .map(|(k, v)| format!("{:?}:{:?}", k, v))
            .collect();
        println!("{}[{}] (leaf={})", indent, keys.join(", "), self.leaf);
        for child in &self.children {
            child.print_tree(depth + 1);
        }
    }

    /// Returns the height of the subtree.
    fn height(&self) -> usize {
        if self.leaf {
            0
        } else {
            1 + self.children[0].height()
        }
    }

    /// Count keys in this subtree.
    fn count(&self) -> usize {
        let mut cnt = self.keys.len();
        for c in &self.children {
            cnt += c.count();
        }
        cnt
    }
}

/// Public B-tree structure
pub struct BTree<K: Ord + Debug + Clone, V: Debug + Clone> {
    root: Option<BTreeNode<K, V>>,
}

impl<K: Ord + Debug + Clone, V: Debug + Clone> BTree<K, V> {
    /// Create a new, empty B-tree.
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        BTree { root: None }
    }

    /// Search for a key, returning Some(&V) if found.
    pub fn search(&self, key: &K) -> Option<&V> {
        self.root.as_ref()?.search(key)
    }

    /// Insert a key-value pair. Updates value if key already exists.
    pub fn insert(&mut self, key: K, value: V) {
        match self.root {
            None => {
                let mut node = BTreeNode::new(true);
                node.keys.push(key);
                node.values.push(value);
                self.root = Some(node);
            }
            Some(ref mut root) if root.is_full() => {
                // Root is full — create a new root and split the old one
                let old_root = self.root.take().unwrap();
                let mut new_root = BTreeNode::new(false);
                new_root.children.push(old_root);
                new_root.split_child(0);
                new_root.insert_non_full(key, value);
                self.root = Some(new_root);
            }
            Some(ref mut root) => {
                root.insert_non_full(key, value);
            }
        }
    }

    /// Delete a key from the tree (no-op if not found).
    pub fn delete(&mut self, key: &K) {
        if let Some(ref mut root) = self.root {
            root.delete(key);

            // If root becomes empty but has a child, shrink the tree height
            if root.keys.is_empty() {
                self.root = if root.leaf {
                    None // Tree is now completely empty
                } else {
                    Some(root.children.remove(0))
                };
            }
        }
    }

    /// Returns whether the key exists in the tree.
    pub fn contains(&self, key: &K) -> bool {
        self.search(key).is_some()
    }

    /// In-order traversal returning all (key, value) pairs sorted by key.
    pub fn traverse(&self) -> Vec<(K, V)> {
        let mut result = Vec::new();
        if let Some(ref root) = self.root {
            root.traverse(&mut result);
        }
        result
    }

    /// Returns true if the tree is empty.
    pub fn is_empty(&self) -> bool {
        self.root.is_none()
    }

    /// Returns the number of key-value pairs stored.
    pub fn len(&self) -> usize {
        self.root.as_ref().map_or(0, |r| r.count())
    }

    /// Returns the height of the tree (0 = single leaf or empty).
    pub fn height(&self) -> usize {
        self.root.as_ref().map_or(0, |r| r.height())
    }

    /// Pretty-print the tree for debugging.
    pub fn print_tree(&self) {
        match &self.root {
            None => println!("<empty tree>"),
            Some(root) => root.print_tree(0),
        }
    }
}

impl<K: Ord + Debug + Clone, V: Debug + Clone> Default for BTree<K, V> {
    fn default() -> Self {
        Self::new()
    }
}

