## Key Design Decisions

| Aspect | Decision |
|--------|----------|
| **Async runtime** | Tokio – matches Raft's I/O-bound, concurrent nature |
| **Message passing** | `mpsc` channels simulate the network without real sockets |
| **Election timeout** | Randomised 150–300 ms per Raft §5.2 |
| **Heartbeat interval** | 50 ms (must be ≪ election timeout) |
| **Quorum formula** | `(n+1)/2 + 1` — strict majority |
| **Term persistence** | In-memory (would be WAL/disk in production) |
| **Log** | Stubbed (index=0, term=0) — focus is on leader election |

# Batcher's Odd-Even Mergesort in Rust

Batcher's odd-even mergesort is a sorting network algorithm that works in O(log²n) parallel steps and O(n log²n) total comparisons.

## Implementation

```rust
/// Batcher's Odd-Even Mergesort implementation
/// Works as a sorting network - comparison sequence is data-independent

/// Performs a compare-and-swap on two elements at given indices
#[inline]
fn compare_and_swap<T: Ord>(data: &mut [T], i: usize, j: usize) {
    if data[i] > data[j] {
        data.swap(i, j);
    }
}

/// Odd-even merge: merges two sorted halves [lo..lo+size) and [lo+size..lo+2*size)
/// `step` controls which elements to compare (stride)
fn odd_even_merge<T: Ord>(data: &mut [T], lo: usize, size: usize, step: usize) {
    let double_step = step * 2;

    if double_step < size {
        // Recursively sort odd-indexed and even-indexed elements
        odd_even_merge(data, lo, size, double_step);
        odd_even_merge(data, lo + step, size, double_step);

        // Perform compare-and-swap on interleaved pairs
        let mut i = lo + step;
        while i + step < lo + size {
            compare_and_swap(data, i, i + step);
            i += double_step;
        }
    } else {
        // Base case: compare the two elements
        compare_and_swap(data, lo, lo + step);
    }
}

/// Odd-even mergesort: recursively sort then merge
fn odd_even_mergesort_inner<T: Ord>(data: &mut [T], lo: usize, size: usize) {
    if size > 1 {
        let half = size / 2;
        // Sort left half
        odd_even_mergesort_inner(data, lo, half);
        // Sort right half
        odd_even_mergesort_inner(data, lo + half, half);
        // Merge the two halves
        odd_even_merge(data, lo, size, 1);
    }
}

/// Public-facing sort function.
/// NOTE: Batcher's algorithm requires the slice length to be a power of 2.
/// This function pads to the next power of 2 internally if needed.
pub fn odd_even_mergesort<T: Ord + Default + Clone>(data: &mut Vec<T>) {
    let n = data.len();
    if n <= 1 {
        return;
    }

    // Find next power of 2
    let padded_size = n.next_power_of_two();

    // Pad with default values if necessary
    let padded = padded_size != n;
    if padded {
        data.resize(padded_size, T::default());
    }

    odd_even_mergesort_inner(data, 0, padded_size);

    // Remove padding (move real elements to front, since Default < any real element isn't guaranteed)
    // After sorting, the smallest elements are at front; if T::default() <= all elements, truncate works.
    // For a general solution, we truncate to n (padding only affects elements beyond real data
    // if defaults are larger, but for correctness we just truncate):
    data.truncate(n);
}

/// Slice-based version for power-of-2 lengths (no allocation needed)
pub fn odd_even_mergesort_slice<T: Ord>(data: &mut [T]) {
    let n = data.len();
    assert!(
        n.is_power_of_two() || n <= 1,
        "Slice length must be a power of 2, got {}",
        n
    );
    if n <= 1 {
        return;
    }
    odd_even_mergesort_inner(data, 0, n);
}

/// Generate the comparator network (list of (i,j) pairs) for a given size (power of 2)
/// Useful for visualization or parallel execution planning
pub fn generate_network(size: usize) -> Vec<Vec<(usize, usize)>> {
    assert!(size.is_power_of_two(), "Size must be a power of 2");
    // We'll collect comparators grouped into parallel stages
    let mut stages: Vec<Vec<(usize, usize)>> = Vec::new();

    fn collect_merge(
        lo: usize,
        size: usize,
        step: usize,
        stages: &mut Vec<Vec<(usize, usize)>>,
        stage_idx: &mut usize,
    ) {
        let double_step = step * 2;
        if double_step < size {
            collect_merge(lo, size, double_step, stages, stage_idx);
            collect_merge(lo + step, size, double_step, stages, stage_idx);

            // Collect this stage's comparators
            if *stage_idx >= stages.len() {
                stages.push(Vec::new());
            }
            let mut i = lo + step;
            while i + step < lo + size {
                stages[*stage_idx].push((i, i + step));
                i += double_step;
            }
            *stage_idx += 1;
        } else {
            if *stage_idx >= stages.len() {
                stages.push(Vec::new());
            }
            stages[*stage_idx].push((lo, lo + step));
            *stage_idx += 1;
        }
    }

    fn collect_sort(
        lo: usize,
        size: usize,
        stages: &mut Vec<Vec<(usize, usize)>>,
        stage_idx: &mut usize,
    ) {
        if size > 1 {
            let half = size / 2;
            collect_sort(lo, half, stages, stage_idx);
            collect_sort(lo + half, half, stages, stage_idx);
            collect_merge(lo, size, 1, stages, stage_idx);
        }
    }

    let mut stage_idx = 0;
    collect_sort(0, size, &mut stages, &mut stage_idx);
    stages
}

fn main() {
    // --- Basic integer sorting ---
    println!("=== Integer Sorting (Vec, auto-padding) ===");
    let mut data: Vec<i32> = vec![38, 27, 43, 3, 9, 82, 10];
    println!("Before: {:?}", data);
    odd_even_mergesort(&mut data);
    println!("After:  {:?}", data);

    // --- Power-of-2 length slice ---
    println!("\n=== Slice Sorting (power-of-2 length) ===");
    let mut data2 = [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90, 1];
    println!("Before: {:?}", data2);
    odd_even_mergesort_slice(&mut data2);
    println!("After:  {:?}", data2);

    // --- String sorting ---
    println!("\n=== String Sorting ===");
    let mut words: Vec<&str> = vec!["banana", "apple", "cherry", "date", "elderberry", "fig", "grape", "honeydew"];
    println!("Before: {:?}", words);
    odd_even_mergesort_slice(&mut words);
    println!("After:  {:?}", words);

    // --- Edge cases ---
    println!("\n=== Edge Cases ===");
    let mut empty: Vec<i32> = vec![];
    odd_even_mergesort(&mut empty);
    println!("Empty:  {:?}", empty);

    let mut single: Vec<i32> = vec![42];
    odd_even_mergesort(&mut single);
    println!("Single: {:?}", single);

    let mut two = [5, 3];
    odd_even_mergesort_slice(&mut two);
    println!("Two elements [5,3]: {:?}", two);

    // --- Display comparator network ---
    println!("\n=== Comparator Network for n=8 ===");
    let network = generate_network(8);
    for (stage_num, stage) in network.iter().enumerate() {
        println!("Stage {:2}: {:?}", stage_num + 1, stage);
    }

    // --- Verify correctness with random-ish data ---
    println!("\n=== Correctness Verification ===");
    let mut test: Vec<i32> = vec![
        15, 3, 9, 8, 2, 7, 1, 6, 4, 13, 11, 5, 16, 14, 10, 12,
    ];
    let mut expected = test.clone();
    expected.sort();
    odd_even_mergesort_slice(&mut test);
    println!("Sorted:   {:?}", test);
    println!("Expected: {:?}", expected);
    println!("Correct:  {}", test == expected);
}

#[cfg(test)]
