## Key Design Decisions

### Architecture

| Component | Role |
|-----------|------|
| `Header<K,V>` | Sentinel node with no key/value, holds top-level forward pointers |
| `Node<K,V>` | Data node with key, value, and level-specific forward pointers |
| `SkipList<K,V>` | Container tracking header, current max level, and length |
| `Iter<'a,K,V>` | Zero-copy iterator traversing level-0 linked list |

### Safety
- Raw pointers (`*mut Node`) are used internally for the multi-level linked structure; all `unsafe` blocks are contained and justified
- `Drop` walks level-0 to free all nodes, preventing leaks
- `Box::from_raw` is used exactly once per node to reclaim ownership

### Complexity

| Operation | Average | Worst Case |
|-----------|---------|------------|
| `insert` | O(log n) | O(n) |
| `get` | O(log n) | O(n) |
| `remove` | O(log n) | O(n) |
| `iter` | O(n) | O(n) |
| Space | O(n log n) | O(n log n) |

# N-Queens Problem in Rust

## Overview
The N-Queens problem places N queens on an N×N chessboard so that no two queens attack each other (no shared row, column, or diagonal).

## Implementation

```rust
fn solve_n_queens(n: usize) -> Vec<Vec<String>> {
    let mut solutions = Vec::new();
    let mut board = vec![0usize; n]; // board[row] = col position of queen

    solve(&mut board, 0, n, &mut solutions);
    solutions
}

fn solve(board: &mut Vec<usize>, row: usize, n: usize, solutions: &mut Vec<Vec<String>>) {
    if row == n {
        solutions.push(board_to_strings(board, n));
        return;
    }

    for col in 0..n {
        if is_safe(board, row, col) {
            board[row] = col;
            solve(board, row + 1, n, solutions);
        }
    }
}

fn is_safe(board: &[usize], row: usize, col: usize) -> bool {
    for r in 0..row {
        let c = board[r];
        // Check same column or diagonal attack
        if c == col || c.abs_diff(col) == row.abs_diff(r) {
            return false;
        }
    }
    true
}

fn board_to_strings(board: &[usize], n: usize) -> Vec<String> {
    board
        .iter()
        .map(|&col| {
            let mut row = ".".repeat(n);
            row.replace_range(col..=col, "Q");
            row
        })
        .collect()
}

fn print_solutions(solutions: &[Vec<String>], n: usize) {
    println!("N = {n}");
    println!("Total solutions: {}", solutions.len());
    println!("{}", "─".repeat(40));

    for (i, solution) in solutions.iter().enumerate() {
        println!("Solution {}:", i + 1);
        for row in solution {
            println!("  {row}");
        }
        println!();
    }
}

fn count_solutions(n: usize) -> usize {
    let mut board = vec![0usize; n];
    count(&mut board, 0, n)
}

fn count(board: &mut Vec<usize>, row: usize, n: usize) -> usize {
    if row == n {
        return 1;
    }
    let mut total = 0;
    for col in 0..n {
        if is_safe(board, row, col) {
            board[row] = col;
            total += count(board, row + 1, n);
        }
    }
    total
}

fn main() {
    // Show all solutions for small N
    for n in 1..=6 {
        let solutions = solve_n_queens(n);
        print_solutions(&solutions, n);
    }

    // Show only solution counts for larger N
    println!("{}", "─".repeat(40));
    println!("Solution counts for larger N:");
    println!("{:<6} {}", "N", "Solutions");
    println!("{}", "─".repeat(20));
    for n in 1..=14 {
        let count = count_solutions(n);
        println!("{:<6} {}", n, count);
    }
}
```

## Key Components

| Function | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `solve_n_queens` | Entry point, returns all board solutions |
| `solve` | Recursive backtracking per row |
| `is_safe` | Validates queen placement (column + diagonals) |
| `board_to_strings` | Converts position array to visual board |
| `count_solutions` | Optimized count-only variant |

## Safety Check Logic

```
c == col                    → same column attack
c.abs_diff(col) == row.abs_diff(r) → diagonal attack
```

Since we place **one queen per row** by design, row conflicts are impossible.

