## Key Design Decisions

| Decision | Reason |
|---|---|
| `mid = low + (high - low) / 2` | Prevents integer overflow compared to `(low + high) / 2` |
| Half-open interval `[low, high)` | Cleaner termination; `high = arr.len()` is always valid |
| `T: Ord` generic bound | Works with any totally ordered type, not just integers |
| Returns `Option<usize>` | Idiomatic Rust — no sentinel values like `-1` |
| `match` on `Ordering` | Exhaustive, readable, and prevents off-by-one mistakes |

# Flatten Nested List in Rust

Here's a complete implementation using a recursive enum to represent nested lists, with multiple flattening approaches:

```rust
/// Represents a nested list that can contain either integers or other nested lists
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
enum NestedList {
    Int(i32),
    List(Vec<NestedList>),
}

impl NestedList {
    /// Flatten the nested list into a Vec<i32>
    fn flatten(&self) -> Vec<i32> {
        match self {
            NestedList::Int(n) => vec![*n],
            NestedList::List(items) => items.iter().flat_map(|item| item.flatten()).collect(),
        }
    }

    /// Flatten in-place using an iterative approach with a stack
    fn flatten_iterative(&self) -> Vec<i32> {
        let mut result = Vec::new();
        let mut stack: Vec<&NestedList> = vec![self];

        while let Some(current) = stack.pop() {
            match current {
                NestedList::Int(n) => result.push(*n),
                NestedList::List(items) => {
                    // Push items in reverse order so we process left-to-right
                    for item in items.iter().rev() {
                        stack.push(item);
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        result
    }
}

/// Flatten a Vec<NestedList> directly
fn flatten_vec(nested: &[NestedList]) -> Vec<i32> {
    nested.iter().flat_map(|item| item.flatten()).collect()
}

/// Generic flatten for Vec<Vec<T>> (one level deep)
fn flatten_one_level<T: Clone>(nested: Vec<Vec<T>>) -> Vec<T> {
    nested.into_iter().flatten().collect()
}

fn main() {
    // Example 1: [1, [2, 3], [4, [5, 6]], 7]
    let nested = NestedList::List(vec![
        NestedList::Int(1),
        NestedList::List(vec![NestedList::Int(2), NestedList::Int(3)]),
        NestedList::List(vec![
            NestedList::Int(4),
            NestedList::List(vec![NestedList::Int(5), NestedList::Int(6)]),
        ]),
        NestedList::Int(7),
    ]);

    println!("Input:              {:?}", nested);
    println!("Recursive flatten:  {:?}", nested.flatten());
    println!("Iterative flatten:  {:?}", nested.flatten_iterative());

    // Example 2: Deeply nested [[[[1], 2], 3], 4]
    let deep = NestedList::List(vec![NestedList::List(vec![NestedList::List(vec![
        NestedList::List(vec![NestedList::Int(1)]),
        NestedList::Int(2),
    ])])]);

    println!("\nDeep nested:        {:?}", deep);
    println!("Recursive flatten:  {:?}", deep.flatten());
    println!("Iterative flatten:  {:?}", deep.flatten_iterative());

    // Example 3: Flat Vec<Vec<i32>> (one level)
    let flat_nested = vec![vec![1, 2], vec![3, 4], vec![5, 6]];
    println!("\nOne-level nested:   {:?}", flat_nested);
    println!("Flattened:          {:?}", flatten_one_level(flat_nested));

    // Example 4: Using flatten_vec helper
    let items = vec![
        NestedList::Int(10),
        NestedList::List(vec![NestedList::Int(20), NestedList::Int(30)]),
    ];
    println!("\nVec flatten:        {:?}", flatten_vec(&items));
}

