## Design Decisions

| Aspect | Choice | Reason |
|--------|--------|--------|
| List nodes | Raw pointers | Doubly-linked lists with safe Rust require `Rc<RefCell<>>` which adds overhead |
| Sentinel nodes | Head + Tail dummies | Eliminates edge cases for empty list / front / back insertions |
| HashMap keys | Clone of K | Required to support lookup by reference and removal during eviction |
| Sentinel init | `MaybeUninit` | Avoids requiring `Default` bounds on `K` and `V` |

## Complexity

| Operation | Time | Space |
|-----------|------|-------|
| `get` | O(1) | O(1) |
| `put` | O(1) | O(1) |
| `remove` | O(1) | O(1) |
| `contains_key` | O(1) | O(1) |
| Total space | — | O(n) |

# Binary Tree Serialization and Deserialization in Rust

## Overview

This implementation serializes a binary tree to a string using level-order (BFS) traversal and deserializes it back. Null nodes are represented as `"#"`.

```rust
use std::collections::VecDeque;
use std::fmt;

// ─────────────────────────────────────────────
// Tree definition
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────

#[derive(Debug, PartialEq, Clone)]
pub struct TreeNode {
    pub val: i32,
    pub left: Option<Box<TreeNode>>,
    pub right: Option<Box<TreeNode>>,
}

impl TreeNode {
    pub fn new(val: i32) -> Self {
        TreeNode {
            val,
            left: None,
            right: None,
        }
    }

    /// Convenience builder – wraps the node in `Some(Box<...>)`.
    pub fn boxed(val: i32) -> Option<Box<Self>> {
        Some(Box::new(Self::new(val)))
    }
}

impl fmt::Display for TreeNode {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter<'_>) -> fmt::Result {
        write!(f, "{}", serialize(Some(self)))
    }
}

// ─────────────────────────────────────────────
// Custom error type
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────

#[derive(Debug, PartialEq)]
pub enum TreeError {
    InvalidToken(String),
    UnexpectedEndOfInput,
}

impl fmt::Display for TreeError {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter<'_>) -> fmt::Result {
        match self {
            TreeError::InvalidToken(t) => write!(f, "Invalid token: '{t}'"),
            TreeError::UnexpectedEndOfInput => write!(f, "Unexpected end of input"),
        }
    }
}

impl std::error::Error for TreeError {}

// ─────────────────────────────────────────────
// Serialization  (tree → string)
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────

/// Serialises `root` with level-order (BFS) traversal.
///
/// Format:  `"1,2,3,#,#,4,5"`
/// Trailing null tokens are omitted to keep the output compact.
pub fn serialize(root: Option<&TreeNode>) -> String {
    let mut tokens: Vec<String> = Vec::new();
    let mut queue: VecDeque<Option<&TreeNode>> = VecDeque::new();

    queue.push_back(root);

    while let Some(node_opt) = queue.pop_front() {
        match node_opt {
            None => tokens.push("#".to_string()),
            Some(node) => {
                tokens.push(node.val.to_string());
                queue.push_back(node.left.as_deref());
                queue.push_back(node.right.as_deref());
            }
        }
    }

    // Strip trailing null markers for a compact representation.
    while tokens.last().map(|t| t == "#").unwrap_or(false) {
        tokens.pop();
    }

    tokens.join(",")
}

// ─────────────────────────────────────────────
// Deserialization  (string → tree)
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────

/// Deserialises a string produced by [`serialize`] back into a binary tree.
///
/// Returns `Ok(None)` for an empty string.
/// Returns `Err(TreeError)` when the input is malformed.
pub fn deserialize(data: &str) -> Result<Option<Box<TreeNode>>, TreeError> {
    let data = data.trim();
    if data.is_empty() {
        return Ok(None);
    }

    let mut tokens = data.split(',');

    // Parse the root token.
    let root_token = tokens.next().ok_or(TreeError::UnexpectedEndOfInput)?;
    let root_node = match root_token {
        "#" => return Ok(None),
        t => parse_token(t)?,
    };

    let mut root = Box::new(root_node);
    // Queue holds mutable references to nodes whose children we still need to fill.
    let mut queue: VecDeque<*mut TreeNode> = VecDeque::new();
    queue.push_back(&mut *root as *mut TreeNode);

    // SAFETY: We process nodes level by level. Each raw pointer in the queue
    // points to a node that is owned by the tree we are constructing. We never
    // alias two mutable references to the same node simultaneously.
    while let Some(node_ptr) = queue.pop_front() {
        let node = unsafe { &mut *node_ptr };

        // ── left child ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
        match tokens.next() {
            None | Some("#") => node.left = None, // no token → implicit null
            Some(t) => {
                let child = Box::new(parse_token(t)?);
                node.left = Some(child);
                queue.push_back(node.left.as_deref_mut().unwrap() as *mut TreeNode);
            }
        }

        // ── right child ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
        match tokens.next() {
            None | Some("#") => node.right = None,
            Some(t) => {
                let child = Box::new(parse_token(t)?);
                node.right = Some(child);
                queue.push_back(node.right.as_deref_mut().unwrap() as *mut TreeNode);
            }
        }
    }

    Ok(Some(root))
}

/// Parses a single numeric token into a [`TreeNode`].
fn parse_token(token: &str) -> Result<TreeNode, TreeError> {
    token
        .trim()
        .parse::<i32>()
        .map(TreeNode::new)
        .map_err(|_| TreeError::InvalidToken(token.to_string()))
}

// ─────────────────────────────────────────────
// Helper: collect values via in-order traversal
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────

pub fn inorder(root: &Option<Box<TreeNode>>) -> Vec<i32> {
    let mut result = Vec::new();
    inorder_helper(root, &mut result);
    result
}

fn inorder_helper(node: &Option<Box<TreeNode>>, acc: &mut Vec<i32>) {
    if let Some(n) = node {
        inorder_helper(&n.left, acc);
        acc.push(n.val);
        inorder_helper(&n.right, acc);
    }
}

