## Key Design Decisions

| Feature | Choice | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| Child storage | `HashMap<char, TrieNode>` | Supports full Unicode; memory-efficient for sparse alphabets |
| Ownership | Nodes own their children | Safe, idiomatic Rust; avoids raw pointers |
| Deletion | Recursive with pruning | Cleans up orphaned nodes automatically |
| `count` field | Words passing through each node | O(1) prefix counting without full traversal |
| Word collection | Sorted output | Deterministic, predictable results |

### Complexity Summary

| Operation | Time | Space |
|---|---|---|
| `insert` | O(m) | O(m) |
| `search` | O(m) | O(1) |
| `starts_with` | O(m) | O(1) |
| `delete` | O(m) | O(1) |
| `words_with_prefix` | O(m + k) | O(k) |
| `count_words_with_prefix` | O(m) | O(1) |

*Where m = word/prefix length, k = number of matching words*

# Permutations in Rust

Here's a complete implementation that generates all permutations of a list using Heap's algorithm, along with a recursive approach for comparison.

## Implementation

```rust
/// Generate all permutations of a slice using Heap's algorithm (iterative)
pub fn permutations_heap<T: Clone>(items: &[T]) -> Vec<Vec<T>> {
    let n = items.len();
    let mut result = Vec::new();
    let mut items = items.to_vec();
    let mut c = vec![0usize; n];

    result.push(items.clone());

    let mut i = 0;
    while i < n {
        if c[i] < i {
            if i % 2 == 0 {
                items.swap(0, i);
            } else {
                items.swap(c[i], i);
            }
            result.push(items.clone());
            c[i] += 1;
            i = 0;
        } else {
            c[i] = 0;
            i += 1;
        }
    }

    result
}

/// Generate all permutations of a slice using recursion
pub fn permutations_recursive<T: Clone>(items: &[T]) -> Vec<Vec<T>> {
    if items.is_empty() {
        return vec![vec![]];
    }

    let mut result = Vec::new();

    for (i, item) in items.iter().enumerate() {
        // Create a slice without the current element
        let remaining: Vec<T> = items
            .iter()
            .enumerate()
            .filter(|&(j, _)| j != i)
            .map(|(_, x)| x.clone())
            .collect();

        // Recursively get permutations of the remaining elements
        for mut perm in permutations_recursive(&remaining) {
            perm.insert(0, item.clone());
            result.push(perm);
        }
    }

    result
}

/// Iterator-based permutation generator (memory efficient for large inputs)
pub struct PermutationIter<T: Clone> {
    items: Vec<T>,
    c: Vec<usize>,
    i: usize,
    first: bool,
}

impl<T: Clone> PermutationIter<T> {
    pub fn new(items: &[T]) -> Self {
        Self {
            items: items.to_vec(),
            c: vec![0; items.len()],
            i: 0,
            first: true,
        }
    }
}

impl<T: Clone> Iterator for PermutationIter<T> {
    type Item = Vec<T>;

    fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item> {
        let n = self.items.len();

        if n == 0 {
            return None;
        }

        // Yield the first permutation without any swaps
        if self.first {
            self.first = false;
            return Some(self.items.clone());
        }

        // Find the next permutation via Heap's algorithm
        while self.i < n {
            if self.c[self.i] < self.i {
                if self.i % 2 == 0 {
                    self.items.swap(0, self.i);
                } else {
                    self.items.swap(self.c[self.i], self.i);
                }
                self.c[self.i] += 1;
                self.i = 0;
                return Some(self.items.clone());
            } else {
                self.c[self.i] = 0;
                self.i += 1;
            }
        }

        None
    }
}

fn main() {
    // --- Heap's Algorithm ---
    println!("=== Heap's Algorithm ===");
    let items = vec![1, 2, 3];
    let perms = permutations_heap(&items);
    println!("Permutations of {:?} ({} total):", items, perms.len());
    for perm in &perms {
        println!("  {:?}", perm);
    }

    // --- Recursive ---
    println!("\n=== Recursive ===");
    let items = vec!['a', 'b', 'c'];
    let perms = permutations_recursive(&items);
    println!("Permutations of {:?} ({} total):", items, perms.len());
    for perm in &perms {
        println!("  {:?}", perm);
    }

    // --- Iterator ---
    println!("\n=== Iterator (lazy) ===");
    let items = vec!["foo", "bar", "baz"];
    let iter = PermutationIter::new(&items);
    println!("Permutations of {:?}:", items);
    for perm in iter {
        println!("  {:?}", perm);
    }

    // --- Edge cases ---
    println!("\n=== Edge Cases ===");
    let empty: Vec<i32> = vec![];
    println!("Empty: {:?}", permutations_heap(&empty));

    let single = vec![42];
    println!("Single element: {:?}", permutations_heap(&single));

    // Count permutations of 4 elements (should be 4! = 24)
    let four = vec![1, 2, 3, 4];
    println!(
        "Count for {:?}: {} (expected {})",
        four,
        permutations_heap(&four).len(),
        24
    );
}

