## Key Concepts

### Algorithm Overview

| Phase | Description | Complexity |
|-------|-------------|------------|
| DP Table Build | Fill `dp[i][j]` with LCS length of prefixes | O(m×n) time, O(m×n) space |
| Backtracking | Trace back through table to reconstruct string | O(m+n) time |
| Space-optimized | Use only 2 rows instead of full table | O(min(m,n)) space |

### Recurrence Relation

```
dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1           if chars1[i-1] == chars2[j-1]
dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]) otherwise
```

### Three Variants Provided

1. **`longest_common_subsequence`** — Returns the LCS string using full DP + backtracking
2. **`lcs_length`** — Returns only the length using space-optimized two-row DP
3. **`all_lcs`** — Returns all possible LCS strings via recursive backtracking with deduplication

### Sample Output

```
Example 1:
  s1: ABCBDAB
  s2: BDCAB
  LCS: "BCAB" (length: 4)

  DP Table:
           B  D  C  A  B
     0  0  0  0  0  0
  A  0  0  0  0  1  1
  B  0  1  1  1  1  2
  C  0  1  1  2  2  2
  B  0  1  1  2  2  3
  D  0  1  2  2  2  3
  A  0  1  2  2  3  3
  B  0  1  2  2  3  4

  All LCS strings:
    "BCAB"
    "BDAB"
```

# Lock-Free Stack in Rust Using Atomics

## Overview

This implements a **Treiber stack** — the classic lock-free stack algorithm using compare-and-swap (CAS) operations. It handles the ABA problem using a generation counter (tagged pointer technique).

## Implementation

```rust
use std::sync::atomic::{AtomicUsize, Ordering};
use std::ptr;
use std::sync::Arc;
use std::thread;

/// A node in the lock-free stack
struct Node<T> {
    data: T,
    next: *mut Node<T>,
}

unsafe impl<T: Send> Send for Node<T> {}
unsafe impl<T: Send> Sync for Node<T> {}

/// Tagged pointer to handle the ABA problem.
/// Uses the lower bits of the pointer for a generation counter.
/// Since nodes are heap-allocated (typically 8-byte aligned),
/// we encode a tag in a separate AtomicUsize alongside the pointer.
#[derive(Debug)]
struct TaggedPtr {
    /// Encodes both pointer address and a tag:
    /// high bits = pointer, low bits = tag (0..TAG_MASK)
    /// We store them in a single usize for atomic CAS.
    ///
    /// On 64-bit systems, user-space pointers only use ~48 bits,
    /// leaving room for a tag in the low bits.
    ///
    /// Alternatively, we use two separate atomics and a SeqLock,
    /// but for simplicity we use pointer tagging here.
    ///
    /// We use a simpler approach: store ptr and tag separately,
    /// using a 128-bit atomic (via AtomicU128) or pack into usize.
    ///
    /// For portability, we pack tag into low 3 bits (alignment guarantee).
    inner: AtomicUsize,
}

const TAG_BITS: usize = 3;
const TAG_MASK: usize = (1 << TAG_BITS) - 1; // 0b111

impl TaggedPtr {
    fn new() -> Self {
        TaggedPtr {
            inner: AtomicUsize::new(0),
        }
    }

    fn pack(ptr: *mut u8, tag: usize) -> usize {
        let addr = ptr as usize;
        debug_assert_eq!(addr & TAG_MASK, 0, "pointer must be aligned");
        addr | (tag & TAG_MASK)
    }

    fn unpack(val: usize) -> (*mut u8, usize) {
        let ptr = (val & !TAG_MASK) as *mut u8;
        let tag = val & TAG_MASK;
        (ptr, tag)
    }

    fn load(&self, order: Ordering) -> (usize, usize) {
        let val = self.inner.load(order);
        let (ptr, tag) = Self::unpack(val);
        (ptr as usize, tag)
    }

    fn compare_exchange(
        &self,
        old_ptr: usize,
        old_tag: usize,
        new_ptr: usize,
        new_tag: usize,
        success: Ordering,
        failure: Ordering,
    ) -> bool {
        let old_val = Self::pack(old_ptr as *mut u8, old_tag);
        let new_val = Self::pack(new_ptr as *mut u8, new_tag & TAG_MASK);
        self.inner
            .compare_exchange(old_val, new_val, success, failure)
            .is_ok()
    }
}

/// Lock-free stack using the Treiber algorithm with ABA protection.
pub struct LockFreeStack<T> {
    head: TaggedPtr,
    _marker: std::marker::PhantomData<T>,
}

// SAFETY: We manage raw pointers carefully with proper synchronization.
unsafe impl<T: Send> Send for LockFreeStack<T> {}
unsafe impl<T: Send> Sync for LockFreeStack<T> {}

impl<T> LockFreeStack<T> {
    /// Create a new empty stack.
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        LockFreeStack {
            head: TaggedPtr::new(),
            _marker: std::marker::PhantomData,
        }
    }

    /// Push a value onto the top of the stack.
    ///
    /// This is wait-free for the allocation step and lock-free for the CAS loop.
    pub fn push(&self, data: T) {
        // Allocate a new node on the heap
        let node = Box::into_raw(Box::new(Node {
            data,
            next: ptr::null_mut(),
        }));

        loop {
            let (head_ptr, head_tag) = self.head.load(Ordering::Acquire);

            // Link the new node to the current head
            unsafe {
                (*node).next = head_ptr as *mut Node<T>;
            }

            // Attempt to swing head to new node, increment tag to prevent ABA
            let new_tag = head_tag.wrapping_add(1);
            if self.head.compare_exchange(
                head_ptr,
                head_tag,
                node as usize,
                new_tag,
                Ordering::Release,
                Ordering::Relaxed,
            ) {
                break;
            }
            // CAS failed: another thread modified head; retry
        }
    }

    /// Pop a value from the top of the stack.
    ///
    /// Returns `None` if the stack is empty.
    pub fn pop(&self) -> Option<T> {
        loop {
            let (head_ptr, head_tag) = self.head.load(Ordering::Acquire);

            if head_ptr == 0 {
                return None; // Stack is empty
            }

            let head_node = head_ptr as *mut Node<T>;

            // Read next pointer BEFORE the CAS
            let next = unsafe { (*head_node).next };

            // Attempt to swing head to next node, increment tag
            let new_tag = head_tag.wrapping_add(1);
            if self.head.compare_exchange(
                head_ptr,
                head_tag,
                next as usize,
                new_tag,
                Ordering::Release,
                Ordering::Relaxed,
            ) {
                // We successfully removed the node — now reclaim it
                // SAFETY: We own this node now (won the CAS race)
                let data = unsafe {
                    let boxed = Box::from_raw(head_node);
                    boxed.data
                };
                return Some(data);
            }
            // CAS failed: retry
        }
    }

    /// Peek at the top element without removing it.
    ///
    /// # Safety
    /// This is inherently racy in a concurrent context. Use only when
    /// you can guarantee no concurrent pops, or for debugging.
    pub fn is_empty(&self) -> bool {
        let (head_ptr, _) = self.head.load(Ordering::Acquire);
        head_ptr == 0
    }
}

impl<T> Drop for LockFreeStack<T> {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        // Drain remaining elements to avoid memory leaks
        while self.pop().is_some() {}
    }
}

impl<T> Default for LockFreeStack<T> {
    fn default() -> Self {
        Self::new()
    }
}

// ─────────────────────────────────────────────
// Iterator support
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────

pub struct IntoIter<T>(LockFreeStack<T>);

impl<T> IntoIterator for LockFreeStack<T> {
    type Item = T;
    type IntoIter = IntoIter<T>;

    fn into_iter(self) -> Self::IntoIter {
        IntoIter(self)
    }
}

impl<T> Iterator for IntoIter<T> {
    type Item = T;

    fn next(&mut self) -> Option<T> {
        self.0.pop()
    }
}

