## How It Works

### Algorithm Breakdown

```
odd_even_mergesort([38, 27, 43, 3, 9, 82, 10, 1])
│
├── sort left  [38, 27, 43, 3]  →  [3, 27, 38, 43]
├── sort right [9, 82, 10, 1]   →  [1, 9, 10, 82]
│
└── odd_even_merge([3,27,38,43], [1,9,10,82])
    ├── merge even-indexed: [3,38] ∪ [1,10]  →  [1,3,10,38]
    ├── merge odd-indexed:  [27,43] ∪ [9,82] →  [9,27,43,82]
    └── swap adjacent pairs: (3,9),(10,27),(38,43) → [1,3,9,10,27,38,43,82]
```

### Key Properties

| Property | Value |
|---|---|
| Time complexity | O(log² n) parallel steps |
| Total comparisons | O(n log² n) |
| Space complexity | O(n log² n) comparator network |
| Stable | No |
| In-place | Yes |

### Parallel vs Sequential

In this sequential implementation the stages run one after another, giving **O(n log² n)** total work. On parallel hardware each *stage* runs in **O(1)** time, giving **O(log² n)** wall-clock time — which is the real advantage of the algorithm.

