## Key Design Decisions

| Layer | Approach |
|---|---|
| **Lexer** | Hand-rolled, single-pass character scanner |
| **Parser** | Recursive-descent; clean separation per clause |
| **Precedence** | `OR` < `AND` < `NOT` < primary (standard SQL) |
| **Error handling** | `Result<T, String>` throughout; errors propagate with `?` |

## Features Supported

- `SELECT *` and named columns
- `table.column` qualified names
- `AS` aliases
- `FROM` table
- `WHERE` with `=`, `!=`, `<>`, `<`, `>`, `<=`, `>=`, `LIKE`
- `IS NULL` / `IS NOT NULL`
- `AND`, `OR`, `NOT` with correct precedence
- Parenthesised sub-expressions
- `ORDER BY col ASC|DESC` (multiple columns)
- `LIMIT n`
- Optional trailing `;`

# Lamport Timestamps in Rust

## Overview

Lamport timestamps provide a logical clock mechanism for ordering events in distributed systems. The algorithm ensures that if event A causally precedes event B, then A's timestamp is less than B's timestamp.

## Implementation

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};
use std::thread;
use std::time::Duration;

/// Lamport clock for a single process
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct LamportClock {
    time: u64,
    process_id: u32,
}

impl LamportClock {
    pub fn new(process_id: u32) -> Self {
        LamportClock {
            time: 0,
            process_id,
        }
    }

    /// Increment clock for a local event
    pub fn tick(&mut self) -> u64 {
        self.time += 1;
        self.time
    }

    /// Update clock when sending a message (returns timestamp to attach)
    pub fn send(&mut self) -> u64 {
        self.time += 1;
        self.time
    }

    /// Update clock when receiving a message with a given timestamp
    pub fn receive(&mut self, received_time: u64) -> u64 {
        self.time = self.time.max(received_time) + 1;
        self.time
    }

    pub fn current_time(&self) -> u64 {
        self.time
    }

    pub fn process_id(&self) -> u32 {
        self.process_id
    }
}

/// A message passed between processes
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct Message {
    pub sender_id: u32,
    pub receiver_id: u32,
    pub timestamp: u64,
    pub payload: String,
}

impl Message {
    pub fn new(sender_id: u32, receiver_id: u32, timestamp: u64, payload: String) -> Self {
        Message {
            sender_id,
            receiver_id,
            timestamp,
            payload,
        }
    }
}

/// An event recorded by a process
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct Event {
    pub process_id: u32,
    pub timestamp: u64,
    pub kind: EventKind,
    pub description: String,
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq)]
pub enum EventKind {
    Internal,
    Send,
    Receive,
}

impl Event {
    /// Total ordering: compare by (timestamp, process_id) to break ties
    pub fn happens_before(&self, other: &Event) -> bool {
        self.timestamp < other.timestamp
            || (self.timestamp == other.timestamp && self.process_id < other.process_id)
    }
}

impl std::fmt::Display for Event {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut std::fmt::Formatter<'_>) -> std::fmt::Result {
        let kind_str = match self.kind {
            EventKind::Internal => "LOCAL",
            EventKind::Send => "SEND ",
            EventKind::Receive => "RECV ",
        };
        write!(
            f,
            "[T={:03}, P={}, {}] {}",
            self.timestamp, self.process_id, kind_str, self.description
        )
    }
}

/// Shared event log for collecting all events across processes
type SharedEventLog = Arc<Mutex<Vec<Event>>>;

/// A simulated distributed process
pub struct Process {
    pub id: u32,
    clock: LamportClock,
    event_log: SharedEventLog,
    /// Channel to send messages to other processes
    /// In real systems this would be a network connection
    message_queues: HashMap<u32, Arc<Mutex<Vec<Message>>>>,
}

impl Process {
    pub fn new(
        id: u32,
        event_log: SharedEventLog,
        message_queues: HashMap<u32, Arc<Mutex<Vec<Message>>>>,
    ) -> Self {
        Process {
            id,
            clock: LamportClock::new(id),
            event_log,
            message_queues,
        }
    }

    /// Perform a local (internal) event
    pub fn local_event(&mut self, description: &str) {
        let ts = self.clock.tick();
        let event = Event {
            process_id: self.id,
            timestamp: ts,
            kind: EventKind::Internal,
            description: description.to_string(),
        };
        println!("  Process {}: {}", self.id, event);
        self.event_log.lock().unwrap().push(event);
    }

    /// Send a message to another process
    pub fn send_message(&mut self, receiver_id: u32, payload: &str) {
        let ts = self.clock.send();
        let msg = Message::new(self.id, receiver_id, ts, payload.to_string());

        let event = Event {
            process_id: self.id,
            timestamp: ts,
            kind: EventKind::Send,
            description: format!("Sending '{}' to P{} (msg_ts={})", payload, receiver_id, ts),
        };
        println!("  Process {}: {}", self.id, event);
        self.event_log.lock().unwrap().push(event);

        // Deliver to receiver's queue
        if let Some(queue) = self.message_queues.get(&receiver_id) {
            queue.lock().unwrap().push(msg);
        }
    }

    /// Check for incoming messages and process them
    pub fn receive_pending_messages(&mut self) {
        let my_queue = self
            .message_queues
            .get(&self.id)
            .cloned()
            .expect("Own queue must exist");

        let messages: Vec<Message> = {
            let mut q = my_queue.lock().unwrap();
            q.drain(..).collect()
        };

        for msg in messages {
            let ts = self.clock.receive(msg.timestamp);
            let event = Event {
                process_id: self.id,
                timestamp: ts,
                kind: EventKind::Receive,
                description: format!(
                    "Received '{}' from P{} (msg_ts={}, local_ts={})",
                    msg.payload, msg.sender_id, msg.timestamp, ts
                ),
            };
            println!("  Process {}: {}", self.id, event);
            self.event_log.lock().unwrap().push(event);
        }
    }

    pub fn current_time(&self) -> u64 {
        self.clock.current_time()
    }
}

/// Sort and display events in Lamport order
pub fn display_ordered_events(event_log: &SharedEventLog) {
    let mut events = event_log.lock().unwrap().clone();

    // Sort by (timestamp, process_id) for total ordering
    events.sort_by(|a, b| {
        a.timestamp
            .cmp(&b.timestamp)
            .then(a.process_id.cmp(&b.process_id))
    });

    println!("\n{}", "=".repeat(60));
    println!("GLOBALLY ORDERED EVENT HISTORY (Lamport Order)");
    println!("{}", "=".repeat(60));
    for (i, event) in events.iter().enumerate() {
        println!("  {:02}. {}", i + 1, event);
    }
    println!("{}", "=".repeat(60));
}

/// Verify happens-before relationships
pub fn verify_causality(event_log: &SharedEventLog) {
    let events = event_log.lock().unwrap().clone();
    println!("\nCAUSALITY VERIFICATION");
    println!("{}", "-".repeat(40));

    let mut violations = 0;
    for i in 0..events.len() {
        for j in (i + 1)..events.len() {
            let a = &events[i];
            let b = &events[j];
            // If timestamps are equal and from same process, that's a bug
            if a.timestamp == b.timestamp && a.process_id == b.process_id {
                println!(
                    "  ⚠ VIOLATION: Same timestamp {} on process {}",
                    a.timestamp, a.process_id
                );
                violations += 1;
            }
        }
    }
    if violations == 0 {
        println!("  ✓ No timestamp violations detected");
        println!("  ✓ Lamport ordering property maintained");
    }
}

fn main() {
    println!("Lamport Timestamp Demonstration");
    println!("{}", "=".repeat(60));

    // Shared event log and message queues
    let event_log: SharedEventLog = Arc::new(Mutex::new(Vec::new()));

    // Create per-process message queues (process_id -> queue)
    let num_processes = 3u32;
    let mut all_queues: HashMap<u32, Arc<Mutex<Vec<Message>>>> = HashMap::new();
    for pid in 0..num_processes {
        all_queues.insert(pid, Arc::new(Mutex::new(Vec::new())));
    }

    // -------------------------------------------------------
    // Scenario: 3 processes with sends, receives, local events
    // -------------------------------------------------------
    println!("\n--- Scenario: Multi-process message passing ---\n");

    // Build processes sharing the queues
    let mut p0 = Process::new(0, Arc::clone(&event_log), all_queues.clone());
    let mut p1 = Process::new(1, Arc::clone(&event_log), all_queues.clone());
    let mut p2 = Process::new(2, Arc::clone(&event_log), all_queues.clone());

    // Simulate distributed execution steps
    // In real distributed systems these happen concurrently;
    // here we interleave them to demonstrate ordering.

    println!("[Step 1] Each process performs local work:");
    p0.local_event("Initialize database");
    p1.local_event("Start worker thread");
    p2.local_event("Load configuration");

    println!("\n[Step 2] P0 sends to P1, P2 does local work:");
    p0.send_message(1, "BEGIN_TRANSACTION");
    p2.local_event("Validate inputs");

    println!("\n[Step 3] P1 receives, then sends to P2:");
    p1.receive_pending_messages();
    p1.send_message(2, "FORWARD_DATA");
    p1.local_event("Update local state");

    println!("\n[Step 4] P0 does more local work:");
    p0.local_event("Log checkpoint");

    println!("\n[Step 5] P2 receives from P1, P0 sends to P2:");
    p2.receive_pending_messages();
    p0.send_message(2, "COMMIT_REQUEST");

    println!("\n[Step 6] P2 processes final message:");
    p2.receive_pending_messages();
    p2.local_event("Commit complete");

    println!("\n[Step 7] P1 sends acknowledgment to P0:");
    p1.send_message(0, "ACK");
    p0.receive_pending_messages();
    p0.local_event("Transaction complete");

    // Display final clock values
    println!("\nFinal clock values:");
    println!("  Process 0: T={}", p0.current_time());
    println!("  Process 1: T={}", p1.current_time());
    println!("  Process 2: T={}", p2.current_time());

    // Display globally ordered history
    display_ordered_events(&event_log);

    // Verify causality
    verify_causality(&event_log);

    // -------------------------------------------------------
    // Demonstration: happens-before relationship
    // -------------------------------------------------------
    println!("\n--- happens_before() demonstration ---");
    let e1 = Event {
        process_id: 0,
        timestamp: 3,
        kind: EventKind::Internal,
        description: "Event A".to_string(),
    };
    let e2 = Event {
        process_id: 1,
        timestamp: 5,
        kind: EventKind::Internal,
        description: "Event B".to_string(),
    };
    let e3 = Event {
        process_id: 2,
        timestamp: 3,
        kind: EventKind::Internal,
        description: "Event C (concurrent with A)".to_string(),
    };

    println!(
        "  A(T=3,P=0) → B(T=5,P=1): {}",
        e1.happens_before(&e2) // true
    );
    println!(
        "  B(T=5,P=1) → A(T=3,P=0): {}",
        e2.happens_before(&e1) // false
    );
    println!(
        "  A(T=3,P=0) → C(T=3,P=2): {} (tie broken by PID)",
        e1.happens_before(&e3) // true, lower PID wins tie
    );
    println!(
        "  C(T=3,P=2) → A(T=3,P=0): {} (tie broken by PID)",
        e3.happens_before(&e1) // false
    );

    // -------------------------------------------------------
    // Demonstrate thread-safe usage
    // -------------------------------------------------------
    println!("\n--- Thread-safe concurrent clock usage ---");
    let shared_clock = Arc::new(Mutex::new(LamportClock::new(99)));

    let handles: Vec<_> = (0..4)
        .map(|i| {
            let clock = Arc::clone(&shared_clock);
            thread::spawn(move || {
                thread::sleep(Duration::from_millis(i * 10));
                let ts = clock.lock().unwrap().tick();
                println!("  Thread {} ticked clock to T={}", i, ts);
            })
        })
        .collect();

    for h in handles {
        h.join().unwrap();
    }

    println!(
        "  Final shared clock T={}",
        shared_clock.lock().unwrap().current_time()
    );
}
