## Key Design Decisions

### Structure

| Component | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `Node<K,V>` | Holds key, value, and forward pointer array |
| `SkipList<K,V>` | Owns a sentinel `head` node and tracks level/length |
| `SkipListIter<'a,K,V>` | Borrows the list and walks level-0 links |

### Algorithm

```
Insert / Search:
  Start at the highest level of the head sentinel
  Walk forward while next.key < target_key
  Drop one level and repeat
  At level 0 we have found the insertion / search point
```

### Complexity

| Operation | Average | Worst Case |
|---|---|---|
| `insert` | O(log n) | O(n) |
| `get` | O(log n) | O(n) |
| `remove` | O(log n) | O(n) |
| `iter` | O(n) | O(n) |
| Space | O(n log n) | O(n log n) |

### Safety Notes

- Raw pointers (`*mut Node`) are used internally for the linked structure; all unsafe blocks are isolated and invariants are carefully maintained.
- `Box::from_raw` is used to reclaim memory on removal and in `Drop`.
- `PhantomData` in the iterator correctly ties the iterator's lifetime to the skip list, preventing use-after-free.

# N-Queens Problem in Rust

## Overview
The N-Queens problem asks us to place N queens on an N×N chessboard so that no two queens threaten each other (no two queens share the same row, column, or diagonal).

## Implementation

```rust
fn solve_n_queens(n: usize) -> Vec<Vec<String>> {
    let mut solutions = Vec::new();
    let mut board = vec![vec!['.'; n]; n];

    // Track which columns and diagonals are under attack
    let mut cols = vec![false; n];
    let mut diag1 = vec![false; 2 * n - 1]; // top-left to bottom-right (row - col + n - 1)
    let mut diag2 = vec![false; 2 * n - 1]; // top-right to bottom-left (row + col)

    backtrack(
        0,
        n,
        &mut board,
        &mut cols,
        &mut diag1,
        &mut diag2,
        &mut solutions,
    );

    solutions
}

fn backtrack(
    row: usize,
    n: usize,
    board: &mut Vec<Vec<char>>,
    cols: &mut Vec<bool>,
    diag1: &mut Vec<bool>,
    diag2: &mut Vec<bool>,
    solutions: &mut Vec<Vec<String>>,
) {
    // All rows filled — we found a valid solution
    if row == n {
        let solution = board
            .iter()
            .map(|r| r.iter().collect::<String>())
            .collect();
        solutions.push(solution);
        return;
    }

    for col in 0..n {
        let d1 = row + n - 1 - col; // top-right to bottom-left diagonal index
        let d2 = row + col;         // top-left to bottom-right diagonal index

        if cols[col] || diag1[d1] || diag2[d2] {
            continue; // Square is under attack, skip
        }

        // Place the queen
        board[row][col] = 'Q';
        cols[col] = true;
        diag1[d1] = true;
        diag2[d2] = true;

        // Recurse to the next row
        backtrack(row + 1, n, board, cols, diag1, diag2, solutions);

        // Remove the queen (backtrack)
        board[row][col] = '.';
        cols[col] = false;
        diag1[d1] = false;
        diag2[d2] = false;
    }
}

fn print_solutions(solutions: &[Vec<String>], n: usize) {
    println!("N = {n}: {} solution(s) found\n", solutions.len());
    for (i, solution) in solutions.iter().enumerate() {
        println!("Solution {}:", i + 1);
        println!("  +{}+", "---+".repeat(n));
        for row in solution {
            print!("  |");
            for ch in row.chars() {
                if ch == 'Q' {
                    print!(" Q |");
                } else {
                    print!("   |");
                }
            }
            println!();
            println!("  +{}+", "---+".repeat(n));
        }
        println!();
    }
}

fn count_solutions(n: usize) -> usize {
    let mut cols = vec![false; n];
    let mut diag1 = vec![false; 2 * n - 1];
    let mut diag2 = vec![false; 2 * n - 1];
    count_backtrack(0, n, &mut cols, &mut diag1, &mut diag2)
}

/// Count-only version — avoids building board strings for better performance
fn count_backtrack(
    row: usize,
    n: usize,
    cols: &mut Vec<bool>,
    diag1: &mut Vec<bool>,
    diag2: &mut Vec<bool>,
) -> usize {
    if row == n {
        return 1;
    }

    let mut count = 0;
    for col in 0..n {
        let d1 = row + n - 1 - col;
        let d2 = row + col;

        if cols[col] || diag1[d1] || diag2[d2] {
            continue;
        }

        cols[col] = true;
        diag1[d1] = true;
        diag2[d2] = true;

        count += count_backtrack(row + 1, n, cols, diag1, diag2);

        cols[col] = false;
        diag1[d1] = false;
        diag2[d2] = false;
    }
    count
}

fn main() {
    // --- Show all solutions for small N ---
    for n in 1..=6 {
        let solutions = solve_n_queens(n);
        print_solutions(&solutions, n);
    }

    // --- Show solution counts for larger N ---
    println!("Solution counts for larger N:");
    println!("{:<6} {}", "N", "Solutions");
    println!("{}", "-".repeat(20));
    for n in 1..=14 {
        let count = count_solutions(n);
        println!("{:<6} {}", n, count);
    }
}
