## Key Design Decisions

| Decision | Rationale |
|---|---|
| `sort_by` + `partial_cmp` | Handles `f64` which doesn't implement `Ord` due to `NaN` |
| Median before `reverse()` | Easier to compute on ascending-sorted slice |
| Population variance (`/ n`) | Use `/ (n-1)` for sample variance (Bessel's correction) |
| Block expression `{ ... }` | Encapsulates mutation while returning multiple values |
| `Option<Stats>` return | Safely handles empty input without panicking |

```rust
use std::f64::consts::PI;

type Complex = (f64, f64);

fn mul(a: Complex, b: Complex) -> Complex {
    (a.0 * b.0 - a.1 * b.1, a.0 * b.1 + a.1 * b.0)
}

fn add(a: Complex, b: Complex) -> Complex {
    (a.0 + b.0, a.1 + b.1)
}

struct QuantumState {
    amplitudes: Vec<Complex>,
    qubits: usize,
}

impl QuantumState {
    fn new(qubits: usize) -> Self {
        let size = 1 << qubits;
        let mut amplitudes = vec![(0.0, 0.0); size];
        amplitudes[0] = (1.0, 0.0);
        Self { amplitudes, qubits }
    }

    fn apply_gate(&mut self, gate: [[Complex; 2]; 2], target: usize) {
        let size = self.amplitudes.len();
        for i in 0..size {
            if i & (1 << target) == 0 {
                let j = i | (1 << target);
                let a = self.amplitudes[i];
                let b = self.amplitudes[j];
                self.amplitudes[i] = add(mul(gate[0][0], a), mul(gate[0][1], b));
                self.amplitudes[j] = add(mul(gate[1][0], a), mul(gate[1][1], b));
            }
        }
    }

    fn hadamard(&mut self, target: usize) {
        let s = 1.0 / 2f64.sqrt();
        self.apply_gate([[(s,0.0),(s,0.0)],[(s,0.0),(-s,0.0)]], target);
    }

    fn rx(&mut self, theta: f64, target: usize) {
        let (c, s) = ((theta/2.0).cos(), (theta/2.0).sin());
        self.apply_gate([[(c,0.0),(0.0,-s)],[(0.0,-s),(c,0.0)]], target);
    }

    fn cnot(&mut self, control: usize, target: usize) {
        let size = self.amplitudes.len();
        for i in 0..size {
            if i & (1 << control) != 0 && i & (1 << target) == 0 {
                let j = i | (1 << target);
                self.amplitudes.swap(i, j);
            }
        }
    }

    fn probabilities(&self) -> Vec<f64> {
        self.amplitudes.iter().map(|a| a.0*a.0 + a.1*a.1).collect()
    }
}

fn main() {
    let mut qs = QuantumState::new(3);
    qs.hadamard(0);
    qs.cnot(0, 1);
    qs.rx(PI / 4.0, 2);

    println!("State probabilities:");
    for (i, p) in qs.probabilities().iter().enumerate() {
        if *p > 1e-6 {
            println!("  |{:0>3b}⟩: {:.4}", i, p);
        }
    }
}
```

**What this implements:**

| Feature | Description |
|---|---|
| `QuantumState` | Stores complex amplitudes for `2^n` states |
| `apply_gate` | Applies a 2×2 unitary to any target qubit |
| `hadamard` | Creates superposition |
| `rx(θ)` | Rotation around X-axis |
| `cnot` | Two-qubit entangling gate |
| `probabilities` | Measures `|amplitude|²` for each basis state |

**Example output:**
```
State probabilities:
  |000⟩: 0.4268
  |001⟩: 0.0732
  |110⟩: 0.4268
  |111⟩: 0.0732
```

The Bell-state entanglement between qubits 0 and 1 is visible in the correlated `|00⟩`/`|11⟩` outcomes, while the `rx` rotation on qubit 2 splits each into unequal probabilities.

